WEBVTT

00:09.385 --> 00:12.512
[♪♪♪]

00:55.347 --> 00:56.931
PHIL:
Somebody asked me today,

00:57.099 --> 01:00.351
"Phil, if you could be anywhere
in the world, where would you
like to be?"

01:00.602 --> 01:03.146
And I said to him,
"Probably right here,

01:03.397 --> 01:06.482
Elko, Nevada."
Our nation's high at 79 today.

01:06.775 --> 01:09.402
Out in California, they're gonna have
some warm weather tomorrow,

01:09.653 --> 01:12.280
gang wars and some very
overpriced real estate.

01:12.531 --> 01:17.285
Up in the Pacific Northwest,
as you can see, they're gonna
have some very, very tall trees.

01:17.536 --> 01:20.079
Clear across the Rockies
and the Great Plains, mostly.

01:20.330 --> 01:22.749
But look out,
here comes trouble.

01:24.918 --> 01:26.377
Oh, boy!

01:26.545 --> 01:28.629
Front coming our way!
Look out!

01:28.797 --> 01:32.383
What's that gonna mean to us
in the Three Rivers area?
One of these big blue things!

01:32.634 --> 01:36.512
This cold, frigid arctic air,
this big mass coming out
of the north.

01:37.431 --> 01:40.683
It's gonna meet up with all this
moisture coming up out of the Gulf.

01:40.851 --> 01:43.352
Gonna mix together at high
altitudes and cause some snow.

01:43.854 --> 01:45.062
Going out on a limb now:

01:45.230 --> 01:48.900
Not gonna hit us here in Pittsburgh.
Gonna push off and hit Altoona.

01:49.067 --> 01:50.359
Phew, close call, folks.

01:50.611 --> 01:52.278
Let's take a look
at the five-day.

01:52.946 --> 01:55.907
As you can see, nothing
to be too scared about.

01:56.408 --> 01:59.869
Bundle up warm, of course,
but I think you can leave
your galoshes at home.

02:00.078 --> 02:04.916
I'm not gonna be here for the 10:00.
Tomorrow is Groundhog Day,
and I'm going out to Punxsutawney

02:05.083 --> 02:07.585
for our country's oldest
groundhog festival.

02:07.836 --> 02:11.047
So as you know, according to
the legend, tomorrow, February 2nd,

02:11.215 --> 02:13.174
if the groundhog wakes
and sees his shadow,

02:13.342 --> 02:16.427
we've got six more weeks
of winter to look forward to.
So keep your fingers crossed.

02:16.595 --> 02:18.763
Sounds like a lot of fun.
You must really enjoy it.

02:18.931 --> 02:21.516
This is your third year
in a row, isn't it, Phil?

02:21.767 --> 02:24.310
Four, Nan. Four.

02:24.478 --> 02:25.645
Thanks, Phil.

02:26.104 --> 02:30.566
Up next, entertainment editor
Diane Kingman looks at sex
and violence in the movies.

02:30.818 --> 02:31.901
Stay with us.

02:32.069 --> 02:34.779
[THEME MUSIC PLAYING
OVER SPEAKERS]

02:34.988 --> 02:36.030
MAN:
And we're clear.

02:36.281 --> 02:38.157
Have fun in
Punxsutawney, Phil.

02:39.159 --> 02:44.163
For your information,
Hairdo, there is a major
network interested in me.

02:44.414 --> 02:47.041
Yeah, that would be the
Home Shopping Network.

02:48.418 --> 02:51.087
Thanks, Larry.
Go wait in the van, will you?

02:51.672 --> 02:54.173
That was nice, Phil.
"Big trees"!

02:54.341 --> 02:57.343
Stop, Kenny. Look, can you
handle the 10 or not?

02:57.511 --> 02:58.553
Yeah, yeah.

02:58.720 --> 03:02.390
Listen, if for any reason
you don't want to rush back,
I can do the 5 tomorrow.

03:02.558 --> 03:05.726
Oh, come on. I wanna
stay an extra second in
Punxsutawney? Please!

03:05.894 --> 03:10.106
Well, Rita thinks it would be
a great idea to stay around
for some of the other events.

03:10.274 --> 03:11.858
You'll get some
incredible footage.

03:12.109 --> 03:14.443
The people and the fun.
The excitement!

03:14.695 --> 03:17.864
You haven't worked with her yet,
have you? She's really nice.

03:18.073 --> 03:21.242
I think she's gonna be
a really good producer.

03:21.493 --> 03:23.911
You guys are
gonna have fun.

03:25.038 --> 03:29.584
Mm-mm! She's fun.
But not my kind of fun.
I will be here for the 5.

03:29.751 --> 03:30.960
Rita.

03:32.671 --> 03:35.798
[DELBERT McCLINTON'S
"WEATHERMAN" PLAYING]

04:32.397 --> 04:34.482
Can you keep a secret, Larry?

04:35.233 --> 04:37.193
I'm probably leaving PBH.

04:37.653 --> 04:40.279
So this will be the last time

04:40.614 --> 04:42.156
we do the Groundhog together.

04:42.950 --> 04:45.493
I don't understand what's wrong
with the Groundhog Festival.

04:45.661 --> 04:47.036
When I worked in San Diego,

04:47.204 --> 04:50.873
I covered the swallows returning
to Capistrano six years in a row.

04:51.541 --> 04:55.711
Someday, somebody's gonna
see me interviewing a groundhog,
think I don't have a future.

04:55.921 --> 04:58.005
I think it's a nice story.

04:58.256 --> 05:01.050
He comes out.
He looks around.

05:01.259 --> 05:03.010
He wrinkles up
his little nose.

05:03.261 --> 05:07.056
He sees his shadow,
he doesn't see his shadow.
It's nice. People like it.

05:07.307 --> 05:09.684
You are new, aren't you?

05:10.394 --> 05:14.313
You know, people like
blood sausage too.
People are morons.

05:14.940 --> 05:16.524
Nice attitude.

05:16.692 --> 05:20.361
I want you to look in the mirror
and see what you look like when
you do that little groundhog thing.

05:20.529 --> 05:22.571
Okay? For me? Once?

05:22.781 --> 05:26.575
He comes out, and there he
looks at his little shadow.

05:27.995 --> 05:29.870
Would you like some
blood sausage? I have some--

05:30.080 --> 05:31.998
I like blood sausage.

05:32.207 --> 05:35.751
[DELBERT McCLINTON'S
"WEATHERMAN" PLAYING]

06:31.266 --> 06:32.808
Rita, I can't stay here.

06:34.352 --> 06:36.062
LARRY:
Prima donna.

06:36.229 --> 06:38.064
What's the matter, Phil?
I hate this place.

06:38.273 --> 06:40.941
I stayed here two years ago.
I was miserable. It's a fleabag.

06:41.151 --> 06:43.778
I'm not staying here.
You're not staying here.

06:44.029 --> 06:45.946
I'm not?
No.

06:46.156 --> 06:49.492
Larry's just dropping me off.
I booked you in a very nice
bed-and-breakfast on Cherry Street.

06:51.286 --> 06:52.411
Great.

06:53.330 --> 06:56.832
You know, I think this
is one of the traits of
a really good producer.

06:57.125 --> 06:58.793
Keep the talent happy.

06:59.211 --> 07:00.503
Anything I can do.

07:00.879 --> 07:03.339
Would you help me
with my pelvic tilt?

07:03.799 --> 07:04.965
[CHUCKLES]

07:05.217 --> 07:08.844
Within reason.
Would you like to come to
dinner with Larry and me?

07:09.554 --> 07:11.555
No, thank you.
I've seen Larry eat.

07:11.723 --> 07:13.057
[CHUCKLES]

07:14.684 --> 07:17.394
You get your sleep.
I'll see you in the morning.

07:18.271 --> 07:19.647
RITA:
Don't be late.

07:21.942 --> 07:23.859
Did he actually call himself
"the talent"?

07:24.027 --> 07:25.444
[BOTH LAUGHING]

07:33.453 --> 07:37.206
[SONNY & CHER'S "I GOT YOU BABE"
PLAYING ON RADIO]

07:52.722 --> 07:54.431
DJ 1 [ON RADIO]:
Okay, campers, rise and shine!

07:54.599 --> 07:57.309
And don't forget your booties,
because it's cold out there!

07:57.477 --> 08:00.437
DJ 2:
It's cold out there every day!
What is this, Miami Beach?

08:00.605 --> 08:04.567
DJ 1: Not hardly! And you know,
you can expect hazardous travel
later today with that--

08:04.734 --> 08:06.360
You know, that blizzard thing.

08:06.528 --> 08:09.822
DJ 2: Oh, that blizzard thing.
That blizzard thing.
Oh, well, here's the report.

08:10.073 --> 08:13.492
The National Weather Service
is calling for a big blizzard thing.

08:13.660 --> 08:17.413
DJ 1: Yes, they are. But you know,
there's another reason why today is
especially exciting--

08:17.581 --> 08:19.373
DJ 2: Especially cold.
DJ 1: Especially cold, okay.

08:19.583 --> 08:21.834
But the big question
on everybody's lips--

08:22.002 --> 08:25.004
DJ 2: Their chapped lips.
DJ 1: On their chapped lips, right.

08:25.172 --> 08:27.882
Do you think Phil's gonna
come out and see his shadow?

08:28.049 --> 08:29.175
DJ 2:
Punxsutawney Phil!

08:29.342 --> 08:31.093
DJ 1:
That's right, woodchuck chuckers!

08:31.261 --> 08:33.095
BOTH:
It's Groundhog Day!

08:33.263 --> 08:35.556
DJ 1:
Get up and check
that hog out there! Hyah!

08:35.724 --> 08:37.183
DJ 2:
Sooey! Sooey! Come here, girl!

08:37.350 --> 08:38.433
[BOTH OINKING]

08:40.352 --> 08:41.520
Morning!
Morning.

08:41.770 --> 08:43.856
You off to see the groundhog?
Yes, I am.

08:44.065 --> 08:46.150
You think it's gonna be
an early spring?

08:46.359 --> 08:48.444
I'm predicting March 21 st.

08:49.446 --> 08:50.905
Good guess!

08:51.364 --> 08:54.783
You know, I think that
actually is the first day of spring.

08:54.993 --> 08:57.494
[CLASSICAL MUSIC
PLAYING ON RADIO]

09:02.042 --> 09:06.045
Did you sleep well, Mr. Connors?
I slept alone, Mrs. Lancaster.

09:07.214 --> 09:08.547
Would you like some coffee?

09:08.798 --> 09:12.426
I don't suppose there's any
possibility of getting an espresso
or cappuccino this morning, is there?

09:12.594 --> 09:15.471
Oh, I really don't know, um...

09:15.639 --> 09:19.308
How to spell espresso or
cappuccino. This looks fine.

09:19.559 --> 09:21.435
I hope you enjoy
the festivities.

09:21.603 --> 09:25.231
Oh, yeah, I'm sure I'm going to.
There's talk of a blizzard.

09:25.815 --> 09:28.943
Well, we may catch a break
and that blizzard's gonna
blow right by us.

09:29.110 --> 09:31.403
All of this moisture
coming up out of the south

09:31.655 --> 09:33.864
by midday is probably gonna
push on to the east of us.

09:34.074 --> 09:37.368
And at high altitudes
it's gonna crystallize and
give us what we call snow.

09:37.535 --> 09:39.078
Probably be some
accumulation.

09:39.287 --> 09:43.082
But here in Punxsutawney,
our high's gonna get up to
about 30 today, teens tonight.

09:43.291 --> 09:47.044
Chance of precipitation,
about 20 percent today,
20 percent tomorrow.

09:47.295 --> 09:50.297
Did you want to talk about
the weather or were you
just making chitchat?

09:51.216 --> 09:54.051
Chitchat.
Okay. See you later.

09:54.594 --> 09:56.178
Bye.

09:56.346 --> 09:59.515
Oh, um, will you be
checking out today,
Mr. Connors?

09:59.724 --> 10:02.059
Chance of departure today,
100 percent.

10:20.245 --> 10:23.789
Phil? Hey, Phil?

10:23.957 --> 10:27.084
Phil? Phil Connors!
Phil Connors, I thought
that was you!

10:27.252 --> 10:28.585
Hi, how you doing?
Thanks for watching.

10:28.753 --> 10:29.795
Hey, hey.

10:29.963 --> 10:34.508
Now, don't you tell me you
don't remember me, because
I sure as heckfire remember you.

10:35.552 --> 10:36.677
Not a chance.

10:36.886 --> 10:38.304
Ned!

10:39.347 --> 10:41.098
Ryerson!

10:41.933 --> 10:43.684
Needlenose Ned.
Ned the Head.

10:43.893 --> 10:46.312
Come on, buddy.
Case Western High!

10:46.521 --> 10:50.441
Ned Ryerson, I did the
whistling-bellybutton trick
at the high school talent show.

10:50.692 --> 10:55.571
Bing! Ned Ryerson, got the
shingles real bad senior year.
Almost didn't graduate.

10:55.780 --> 10:57.740
Bing again!

10:57.949 --> 11:02.036
Ned Ryerson, I dated your sister,
Mary Pat, a couple times till you
told me not to anymore.

11:02.245 --> 11:03.537
Well?

11:04.372 --> 11:06.457
Ned Ryerson?
Bing!

11:06.708 --> 11:08.000
Bing.

11:08.835 --> 11:11.754
So did you turn pro with that
bellybutton thing, Ned, or what?

11:11.963 --> 11:13.339
No, Phil.
I sell insurance.

11:13.590 --> 11:15.841
What a shock.
Do you have life insurance?

11:16.051 --> 11:18.010
Because if you do, you could
always use a little more.

11:18.219 --> 11:21.388
Am I right or am I right or am
I right? Right? Right? Right?

11:21.806 --> 11:25.642
Ned, I would love to stand here
and talk with you.

11:25.852 --> 11:28.354
But I'm not going to.
See you.

11:28.605 --> 11:30.439
Hey, that's all right!
I'll walk with you.

11:30.648 --> 11:33.567
You know, whenever
I see an opportunity now,
I charge it like a bull.

11:33.818 --> 11:35.652
Ned the Bull,
that's me now.

11:35.904 --> 11:39.448
You know, I got friends
of mine who live and die
by the actuarial tables.

11:39.699 --> 11:42.743
And I say, hey, it's all
one big crapshoot anyhoo.

11:42.952 --> 11:45.079
Tell me, have you ever heard
of single-premium life?

11:45.246 --> 11:47.873
Because I think that really
could be the ticket for you.

11:48.124 --> 11:49.541
Oh, God!

11:49.793 --> 11:53.712
It is so good to see you!
What are you doing for dinner?

11:53.963 --> 11:55.255
Something else.

11:55.465 --> 11:58.967
It's been great seeing you,
Needlehead. Take care.

11:59.719 --> 12:01.512
Whoa-ho-ho-ho!

12:01.679 --> 12:02.971
[LAUGHING]

12:03.139 --> 12:06.767
Watch out for that
first step. It's a doozy!

12:10.480 --> 12:14.024
[FRANKIE YANKOVIC'S
"PENNSYLVANIA POLKA"
PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS]

12:20.490 --> 12:22.991
[CROWD CHATTERING]

12:35.672 --> 12:38.590
RITA:
Hey, Phil! Phil, over here!

12:38.925 --> 12:40.300
Where have you been?

12:40.552 --> 12:42.094
It was horrible.

12:42.345 --> 12:44.263
A giant leech got me.

12:44.639 --> 12:47.099
You're missing all the fun.
These people are great!

12:47.267 --> 12:48.934
Some of them have
been partying all night long.

12:49.102 --> 12:52.563
They sing songs till they get
too cold, and then they go sit
by the fire and they get warm.

12:52.730 --> 12:56.024
And then they come back
and they sing some more.

12:56.192 --> 12:59.069
Yeah. They're hicks, Rita.

12:59.946 --> 13:02.239
So, did you sleep okay
without me?

13:02.490 --> 13:04.241
You tossed and turned,
didn't you?

13:04.451 --> 13:05.659
You're incredible.

13:05.994 --> 13:07.119
Who told you?

13:07.328 --> 13:08.996
[CROWD CHEERING]

13:09.164 --> 13:10.414
Okay. It's groundhog time.

13:14.252 --> 13:16.044
Okay. On me in three,

13:16.254 --> 13:17.963
two, one.

13:18.923 --> 13:23.677
Once a year, the eyes of the nation
turn to this tiny hamlet in Western
Pennsylvania

13:23.928 --> 13:25.554
to watch a master at work.

13:25.763 --> 13:28.307
The master?
Punxsutawney Phil,

13:28.558 --> 13:31.852
the world's most famous
weatherman. The groundhog.

13:32.103 --> 13:36.231
Who, as legend has it,
can predict the coming
of an early spring.

13:36.483 --> 13:39.151
So I guess the question we have
to ask ourselves today is,

13:39.402 --> 13:41.403
"Does Phil feel lucky?"

13:43.531 --> 13:47.659
It's the same old shtick every year.
The guy comes out with a big stick
and raps on the door.

13:47.869 --> 13:50.621
They pull the little rat out,
they talk to him.

13:50.872 --> 13:54.166
The rat talks back.
And then they tell us
what's gonna happen.

13:55.502 --> 13:58.003
[BAND PLAYING
"FOR HE'S A JOLLY GOOD FELLOW"]

14:00.590 --> 14:02.382
RITA:
Aw, isn't he cute?

14:03.468 --> 14:07.846
Hey, do you like the guys
with the prominent upper teeth?

14:08.014 --> 14:09.056
No.

14:09.307 --> 14:10.682
[GIBBERING]

14:12.435 --> 14:12.935
[GROUNDHOG CHITTERING]

14:12.936 --> 14:13.894
[GROUNDHOG CHITTERING]

14:18.358 --> 14:22.277
This February 2nd,
at 7:20 and 30 seconds,

14:22.487 --> 14:25.739
Punxsutawney Phil,
the seer of seers,

14:25.990 --> 14:28.951
prognosticator
of prognosticators,

14:29.244 --> 14:32.454
emerged reluctantly
but alertly

14:32.664 --> 14:34.706
in Punxsutawney, PA,

14:35.041 --> 14:37.626
and stated in groundhog-ese,

14:37.877 --> 14:40.045
"I definitely see a shadow."

14:40.255 --> 14:41.964
[CROWD GROANING]

14:42.924 --> 14:46.718
Sorry, folks.
Six more weeks of winter.

14:46.928 --> 14:49.429
[CROWD SHOUTING AND BOOING]

14:52.183 --> 14:54.977
On me in three, two, one.

14:56.354 --> 14:58.647
This is one time where
television really fails

14:58.856 --> 15:03.193
to capture the true excitement
of a large squirrel predicting
the weather.

15:03.444 --> 15:05.445
I, for one, am very grateful
to have been here.

15:05.613 --> 15:09.658
From Punxsutawney,
this is Phil Connors. So long.

15:09.867 --> 15:12.035
Okay, want to try it again
without the sarcasm?

15:12.287 --> 15:14.830
We got it. I'm out of here.

15:15.707 --> 15:17.374
Prima donnas.

15:17.584 --> 15:19.668
[♪♪♪]

15:30.096 --> 15:32.681
Oh, boy.
Take a look at this.

15:33.808 --> 15:35.475
What is going on?

15:35.685 --> 15:39.646
I don't know, Phil. Perhaps
it's that giant blizzard we're
not supposed to get.

15:39.939 --> 15:41.231
This is impossible.

15:41.399 --> 15:43.525
Hey, hey, hey.
No, no, no.

15:43.693 --> 15:46.778
Nobody honks this horn
but me, okay, pal?

15:50.742 --> 15:53.744
No, no!

15:58.833 --> 16:00.292
[HORN HONKS]

16:08.176 --> 16:09.676
You gotta take this thing
out of here.

16:10.386 --> 16:12.512
Hey, commander,
what's going on?

16:12.764 --> 16:14.890
There's nothing going on.
We're closing the road.

16:15.141 --> 16:18.727
Big blizzard moving in.
What blizzard? It's a couple of flakes.

16:18.936 --> 16:21.647
Don't you listen to the weather?
We got a major storm here.

16:21.981 --> 16:23.857
I make the weather.

16:24.067 --> 16:29.071
All of this moisture coming up
out of the Gulf is gonna push off
to the east and hit Altoona.

16:29.364 --> 16:31.782
Pal, you got that moisture
on your head.

16:32.075 --> 16:33.992
Now, you can go back
to Punxsutawney,

16:34.661 --> 16:37.537
or you can go ahead
and freeze to death.
It's your choice.

16:37.872 --> 16:39.915
So, what's it gonna be?

16:40.083 --> 16:42.584
[HORNS HONKING
AND SIRENS WAILING]

16:42.752 --> 16:44.044
I'm thinking.

16:44.671 --> 16:48.256
Come on, all the long-distance
lines are down?

16:49.092 --> 16:50.550
What about the satellite?

16:50.802 --> 16:52.719
Is it snowing in space?

16:53.888 --> 16:59.101
Don't you have some kind of a line
that you keep open for emergencies
or for celebrities?

16:59.352 --> 17:02.729
I'm both.
I'm a celebrity in an emergency.

17:03.356 --> 17:05.732
Can you patch me through
on that line, please?

17:12.990 --> 17:16.201
Could I have one more of these
with some booze in it, please?

17:17.328 --> 17:20.163
Ooh, I like it here.
Phil.

17:20.373 --> 17:22.374
Going to the
groundhog dinner?

17:22.625 --> 17:24.334
No, I had groundhog
for lunch.

17:24.544 --> 17:26.837
Wasn't bad.
Tastes like chicken.

17:27.046 --> 17:28.714
You two run along.

17:28.881 --> 17:31.800
Wow, Larry.
Looking foxy tonight, man.

17:31.968 --> 17:34.928
Hey, uh, is your troop gonna be
selling cookies again this year?

17:35.096 --> 17:37.597
Oh, ha-ha-ha.
That's so funny, Phil.

17:37.932 --> 17:39.307
So, what are you gonna do?

17:39.851 --> 17:42.102
Uh, I think I'm gonna
go back to my room

17:42.270 --> 17:45.856
and take a hot shower
and maybe read a little
Hustler or something.

17:46.065 --> 17:47.482
Suit yourself.

17:50.903 --> 17:53.321
[PHIL GASPING]

18:00.621 --> 18:02.706
[SCREAMING]

18:06.127 --> 18:08.795
Yo, mom.
Isn't there any hot water?

18:08.963 --> 18:11.298
Oh, no, there wouldn't be today.

18:11.549 --> 18:14.009
Of course not. Silly me.

18:14.218 --> 18:15.677
Sweet dreams.

18:20.141 --> 18:23.685
["I GOT YOU BABE"
PLAYING ON RADIO]

18:39.368 --> 18:41.203
DJ 1:
Okay, campers, rise and shine!

18:41.370 --> 18:44.039
And don't forget your booties,
because it's cold out there!

18:44.207 --> 18:47.083
DJ 2:
It's cold out there every day!
What is this, Miami Beach?

18:47.251 --> 18:48.835
DJ 1: Not hardly!
Nice going, boys.

18:49.003 --> 18:51.421
You're playing yesterday's tape.

18:51.589 --> 18:53.006
DJ 1:
You know, that blizzard thing.

18:53.174 --> 18:56.176
DJ 2: Oh, that blizzard thing.
That blizzard thing.
Oh, well, here's the report.

18:56.385 --> 19:00.180
The National Weather Service
is calling for a big blizzard thing.

19:00.348 --> 19:04.100
DJ 1: Yes, they are. But you know,
there's another reason why today
is especially exciting--

19:04.310 --> 19:06.186
DJ 2: Especially cold.
DJ 1: Especially cold, okay.

19:06.354 --> 19:08.480
But the big question
on everybody's lips--

19:08.648 --> 19:09.940
DJ 2: Their chapped lips.
Chapped lips.

19:10.107 --> 19:11.608
DJ 1:
Their chapped lips, right.

19:11.776 --> 19:14.611
Do you think Phil's gonna
come out and see his shadow?

19:14.779 --> 19:16.029
DJ 2:
Punxsutawney Phil!

19:16.197 --> 19:18.031
DJ 1:
That's right, woodchuck chuckers!

19:18.199 --> 19:19.825
BOTH:
It's Groundhog Day!

19:20.034 --> 19:22.244
DJ 1:
Get up and check
that hog out there! Hyah!

19:22.411 --> 19:23.870
DJ 2:
Sooey! Sooey! Come here, girl!

19:24.038 --> 19:25.497
[BOTH OINKING]

19:26.958 --> 19:28.500
What the hell?

19:29.293 --> 19:31.378
[♪♪♪]

19:36.551 --> 19:39.469
Morning! Off to see
the groundhog?

19:40.263 --> 19:42.848
Yeah.
Think it'll be an early spring?

19:43.724 --> 19:45.600
Didn't we do this
yesterday?

19:46.143 --> 19:47.477
I don't know what you mean.

19:47.645 --> 19:50.772
Ah!
Don't mess with me, Pork Chop!

19:50.940 --> 19:54.067
What day is this?
It's February 2nd.

19:54.402 --> 19:55.861
Groundhog Day.

19:56.863 --> 19:58.530
Yeah.

19:58.781 --> 20:01.032
I'm sorry. You know,
I thought it was yesterday.

20:01.200 --> 20:02.993
[LAUGHING]

20:03.160 --> 20:04.828
[CHUCKLING]

20:09.292 --> 20:11.376
[♪♪♪]

20:17.300 --> 20:20.010
[CLASSICAL MUSIC
PLAYING ON RADIO]

20:24.140 --> 20:26.224
Did you sleep well, Mr. Connors?

20:26.809 --> 20:28.518
Did I sleep well?

20:28.811 --> 20:30.478
Would you like some coffee?

20:30.730 --> 20:33.398
Yes, please.
I think I'll have a double.

20:33.691 --> 20:36.067
I hope you enjoy
the festivities.

20:36.485 --> 20:38.737
There's talk of a blizzard.

20:41.407 --> 20:43.575
Do you ever have déjà vu,
Mrs. Lancaster?

20:43.826 --> 20:46.453
I don't think so,
but I could check
with the kitchen.

20:46.746 --> 20:48.622
No, that's okay. Thank you.

20:50.082 --> 20:52.751
Will you be checking out
today, Mr. Connors?

20:55.046 --> 20:59.341
I'd say the chance
of departure is 80 percent.

21:00.551 --> 21:02.260
Seventy-five, 80.

21:04.639 --> 21:07.015
[♪♪♪]

21:07.475 --> 21:08.934
PHIL:
Excuse me!

21:09.727 --> 21:11.978
Excuse me.
Where's everybody going?

21:12.563 --> 21:14.022
To Gobbler's Knob.

21:14.231 --> 21:15.482
It's Groundhog Day.

21:16.317 --> 21:18.735
It's still just once a year, isn't it?

21:26.118 --> 21:28.119
Hey! Phil?

21:28.329 --> 21:30.330
Phil? Hey!

21:31.040 --> 21:33.375
Phil Connors!
I thought that was you!

21:33.626 --> 21:35.877
My, oh, my,
Phil Connors!

21:36.128 --> 21:40.048
Now, don't you say you don't
remember me, because I sure
as heckfire remember you.

21:40.257 --> 21:42.759
Well?
Ned Ryerson?

21:43.010 --> 21:46.346
Bing! Oh, first shot
right out of the box!

21:46.555 --> 21:49.224
So how's it going, old buddy?

21:49.392 --> 21:52.268
Well, to tell you the truth,
Neddie, I'm not feeling real well.
Would you excuse me?

21:52.436 --> 21:57.357
You know, it's funny you should
mention your health. Because you
will never guess what I do now.

21:57.608 --> 21:58.984
Do you sell insurance?

21:59.151 --> 22:02.737
Ho-ho, bing again!
You are sharp as a tack today!

22:02.989 --> 22:04.823
Do you have
life insurance, Phil?

22:05.074 --> 22:07.367
Because if you do, you could
always use a little more.

22:07.618 --> 22:09.536
Right! I mean,
who couldn't?

22:09.704 --> 22:11.121
But you wanna know something?

22:11.372 --> 22:12.622
I gots a feeling--

22:12.790 --> 22:13.832
[WHISTLES]

22:14.000 --> 22:15.291
--you ain't got any.

22:15.543 --> 22:18.378
Am I right or am I right
or am I right? Am I right?

22:18.587 --> 22:20.171
I gotta go.
Phil--

22:21.382 --> 22:24.259
Whoa-ho-ho-ho!

22:24.427 --> 22:27.637
Watch out for that
first step. It's a doozy!

22:27.805 --> 22:29.639
[LAUGHING]

22:30.224 --> 22:33.351
["PENNSYLVANIA POLKA"
PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS]

22:52.371 --> 22:55.415
RITA:
Phil! Phil, over here!

22:57.585 --> 23:00.253
Where have you been?
Rita. Do me a favor.

23:00.463 --> 23:03.590
I need someone to give me a
good, hard slap in the face.

23:05.259 --> 23:07.719
How's that?
Good.

23:08.220 --> 23:11.681
If you need any help
with the other cheek,
let me know, I'm right here.

23:13.267 --> 23:14.809
Something's going on.
I don't know what to do.

23:15.102 --> 23:17.771
Are you drunk or something?
Drunk's more fun.

23:18.022 --> 23:20.023
Can I be serious with you
for a minute?

23:20.232 --> 23:21.357
I don't know, can you?

23:21.567 --> 23:23.401
Yes, I'm being serious!

23:23.652 --> 23:27.655
I'm having a problem.
I may be having a problem.

23:27.865 --> 23:30.116
Rita, Rita.
It's groundhog time.

23:30.326 --> 23:32.577
See? I knew you
were gonna say that.

23:32.995 --> 23:36.206
I really feel weird.

23:36.457 --> 23:38.750
Let's just do this, Phil.
Then we'll talk.

23:40.961 --> 23:42.545
All right, on me in three,

23:43.047 --> 23:44.589
two, one.

23:45.216 --> 23:48.510
Well, it's Groundhog Day, again,

23:48.761 --> 23:51.638
and that must mean that we're
up here at Gobbler's Knob

23:51.889 --> 23:55.642
waiting for the forecast
from the world's most famous
groundhog weatherman,

23:55.851 --> 23:57.185
Punxsutawney Phil,

23:57.436 --> 24:00.814
who's just about to tell us how
much more winter we can expect.

24:00.981 --> 24:03.566
CROWD [CHANTING]:
Phil! Phil! Phil!

24:07.113 --> 24:08.488
This is a riot!

24:09.657 --> 24:11.866
[BAND PLAYING
"FOR HE'S A JOLLY GOOD FELLOW"]

24:12.034 --> 24:13.201
RITA:
Aw, isn't he cute?

24:13.410 --> 24:14.577
[CROWD CHEERING]

24:14.745 --> 24:18.206
BUSTER:
This February 2nd,
at 7:20 and 30 seconds,

24:18.791 --> 24:22.127
Punxsutawney Phil,
the seer of seers,

24:22.670 --> 24:25.213
prognosticator
of prognosticators,

24:25.714 --> 24:27.423
emerged reluctantly
Phil!

24:27.675 --> 24:29.926
but alertly in Punxsu--

24:30.970 --> 24:33.847
PHIL:
Ha! Whoo! Oh, my gosh!

24:34.014 --> 24:36.224
[PHIL GASPING]

24:37.059 --> 24:39.060
Yeah, Sport,
I know there's a blizzard.

24:39.311 --> 24:42.397
When are the long-distance
lines gonna be repaired?

24:44.275 --> 24:48.444
Well, what if there is no tomorrow?
There wasn't one today.

24:49.947 --> 24:50.989
Hello?

24:51.157 --> 24:52.198
[DIAL TONE]

24:52.366 --> 24:54.075
Hello?

25:04.211 --> 25:06.296
[♪♪♪]

25:22.146 --> 25:25.690
["I GOT YOU BABE"
PLAYING ON RADIO]

25:42.416 --> 25:44.250
[♪♪♪]

25:45.544 --> 25:46.586
Morning!

25:46.795 --> 25:48.338
Off to see the groundhog?

25:54.470 --> 25:57.013
Oh, did you
sleep well, Mr.--?

26:07.691 --> 26:08.983
Ah!

26:09.777 --> 26:11.319
Hey! Phil?

26:11.487 --> 26:14.906
Phil Connors! I thought--
Whoa! Hey, Phil!

26:15.074 --> 26:18.326
Don't say you don't
remember me, because I sure
as heckfire remember you!

26:18.535 --> 26:20.620
It's me, Ned! Ryerson!

26:20.829 --> 26:23.331
Needlenose Ned! Ned the Head!
Come on, buddy, Case Western--

26:24.250 --> 26:25.875
Hey, look-- Hey!

26:26.085 --> 26:27.752
["PENNSYLVANIA POLKA"
PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS]

26:27.920 --> 26:30.880
RITA:
Phil! Phil, over here!

26:31.548 --> 26:33.091
Where have you been?
Can I talk to you

26:33.259 --> 26:34.592
about a matter that is
not work-related?

26:34.760 --> 26:37.011
You never talk about work.
We really have to talk. Come on.

26:37.179 --> 26:38.930
LARRY: Hey!
It's a creative meeting. Forget it.

26:39.098 --> 26:40.974
Wait a second,
we've got work to do.

26:41.141 --> 26:43.685
No, I don't.
I've already done it twice.

26:43.936 --> 26:46.688
Now, when you get finished,
come and meet me in the diner.

26:46.855 --> 26:48.564
Phil!

26:49.358 --> 26:52.443
What's that all about?
I don't know.

26:52.695 --> 26:54.279
Prima donnas.

26:57.866 --> 26:58.908
More coffee, hon?

26:59.076 --> 27:02.912
No, thanks. Just the check, please.
These sticky buns are just heaven.

27:03.122 --> 27:04.247
Aren't they?

27:04.415 --> 27:05.832
[DISHES CLATTERING]

27:06.000 --> 27:08.459
GUS:
Oh, jeez, just put that
anywhere, pal! Yeah!

27:08.669 --> 27:09.836
RALPH:
Good save!

27:10.004 --> 27:11.713
[BOTH APPLAUDING
AND LAUGHING]

27:11.880 --> 27:15.216
Okay, now tell me why
you're too sick to work,
and it better be good.

27:16.385 --> 27:21.306
Rita, I'm reliving
the same day over and over.

27:21.682 --> 27:24.017
Groundhog Day. Today.

27:24.601 --> 27:26.394
Okay. I'm waiting
for the punch line.

27:26.562 --> 27:30.940
No. Really.
This is the third time.

27:31.191 --> 27:33.151
It's like yesterday
never happened.

27:33.610 --> 27:37.363
I am racking my brain, but I can't
even begin to imagine why you'd
make up something like this.

27:38.282 --> 27:40.950
I'm not making it up.
I am asking you for help!

27:41.618 --> 27:43.494
Okay, what do you want me to do?

27:43.704 --> 27:47.040
I don't know! You're a producer.
Come up with something.

27:47.249 --> 27:49.876
You want my advice?
I think you should get
your head examined

27:50.127 --> 27:53.421
if you expect me to believe
a stupid story like that, Phil!

27:53.714 --> 27:55.423
Phil? Like the groundhog Phil?

27:55.758 --> 27:58.343
Yeah. Like the groundhog Phil.

27:58.635 --> 28:01.262
Ha-ha-ha! Look out
for your shadow there, pal!

28:02.014 --> 28:03.973
Morons, your bus is leaving.

28:05.059 --> 28:08.686
You guys ready? We'd better
get going if we're gonna stay
ahead of the weather.

28:08.937 --> 28:10.897
Let's talk about it
back in Pittsburgh.

28:11.065 --> 28:13.483
I'm not going
back to Pittsburgh.

28:13.776 --> 28:15.985
RITA: Why not?
PHIL: Because of the blizzard!

28:16.278 --> 28:18.488
I thought you said that
was gonna hit Altoona.

28:18.655 --> 28:21.574
Yeah, I know
that's what I said.

28:22.242 --> 28:24.285
Phil, I think
you need help.

28:25.079 --> 28:28.164
That's what I've been
saying, Rita. I need help.

28:29.041 --> 28:30.792
Well, no spots.

28:31.043 --> 28:33.503
No clots, no tumors.

28:33.754 --> 28:35.129
No lesions.

28:35.339 --> 28:36.923
No aneurysms.

28:37.091 --> 28:38.716
At least none that
I can see, Mr. Connors.

28:38.967 --> 28:42.845
Of course, if you want a CAT scan
or an MRI, you're gonna have to go
into Pittsburgh.

28:43.055 --> 28:45.264
I can't go
into Pittsburgh.

28:45.516 --> 28:48.726
Why can't you go into Pittsburgh?
I told you, there's a blizzard.

28:48.894 --> 28:50.561
Oh, right. The blizzard.

28:50.813 --> 28:53.731
You know what you
may need, Mr. Connors?

28:54.274 --> 28:55.608
A biopsy.

28:56.068 --> 28:57.860
A psychiatrist.

28:59.530 --> 29:03.408
That's an unusual problem,
Mr. Connors.

29:05.244 --> 29:09.914
Most of my work is with couples,
families. I have an alcoholic now.

29:12.251 --> 29:13.793
Well, you went to college, right?

29:13.961 --> 29:16.546
I mean, it wasn't veterinary
psychology, was it?

29:16.797 --> 29:19.757
Didn't you take some kind of course
that covered this stuff?

29:19.967 --> 29:22.468
Yeah. Sort of, I guess.

29:24.138 --> 29:25.888
Abnormal psychology.

29:26.306 --> 29:28.266
So...

29:29.393 --> 29:30.685
what do I do?

29:31.520 --> 29:32.854
I think we should meet again.

29:33.814 --> 29:35.815
How's tomorrow for you?

29:38.569 --> 29:39.944
Is that not good?

29:44.700 --> 29:47.827
[SUSIE STEVENS' "TAKE ME ROUND
AGAIN" PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS]

29:50.789 --> 29:53.583
I was in the Virgin Islands once.

29:53.834 --> 29:55.835
I met a girl.

29:56.044 --> 29:57.336
We ate lobster.

29:57.588 --> 29:59.589
Drank piña coladas.

29:59.840 --> 30:02.383
At sunset, we made love
like sea otters.

30:06.221 --> 30:08.556
That was a pretty good day.

30:08.807 --> 30:10.641
Why couldn't I get that day

30:10.851 --> 30:14.395
over and over and over?

30:14.688 --> 30:18.566
You know, some guys
would look at this glass
and they would say,

30:18.775 --> 30:20.234
"That glass is half empty."

30:20.486 --> 30:24.280
Other guys would say,
"That glass is half full."

30:24.531 --> 30:27.867
I peg you as a "glass is half empty"
kind of guy. Am I right?

30:29.870 --> 30:33.206
What would you do if you were
stuck in one place,

30:33.457 --> 30:37.376
and every day was exactly the same,
and nothing that you did mattered?

30:39.963 --> 30:42.715
That about
sums it up for me.

30:50.307 --> 30:51.349
Good luck.

30:51.558 --> 30:52.975
I'll drop you off.

30:55.145 --> 30:57.355
This thing sticks a little bit.

30:57.606 --> 30:59.106
You gotta jiggle it--

30:59.358 --> 31:01.526
Come on up here, pal.

31:01.735 --> 31:04.195
Come on, give me your keys, pal.
Give me the keys.

31:04.404 --> 31:07.156
Friends don't let friends drive, right?
Come on, stand up here.

31:07.366 --> 31:10.117
Take a deep breath.
You feel okay? Really?

31:10.285 --> 31:11.953
Okay, you're all right.

31:16.041 --> 31:17.917
Uh-oh. Whoa.

31:18.460 --> 31:21.128
You wanna throw up here
or you wanna throw up in the car?

31:21.505 --> 31:23.422
I think, both.

31:23.590 --> 31:25.091
[CAR ENGINE STARTS]

31:25.259 --> 31:26.467
Come on.

31:27.386 --> 31:29.095
[TYRES SCREECHING]

31:35.227 --> 31:36.811
I really don't think
I should be driving.

31:36.979 --> 31:39.313
No, no. I don't either.

31:39.565 --> 31:40.940
Watch your head.

31:41.149 --> 31:43.150
Watch your knees.
Don't break anything.

31:43.318 --> 31:46.696
All right. Hey, let's
not forget seat belts.

31:47.781 --> 31:51.784
Hey, who else could go for
some flapjacks right now?

31:52.077 --> 31:54.161
[♪♪♪]

31:57.040 --> 31:58.749
Let me ask you guys a question.

31:59.001 --> 32:00.543
GUS:
Shoot.

32:01.378 --> 32:03.379
What if there were no tomorrow?

32:03.922 --> 32:09.010
No tomorrow? That would mean
there would be no consequences,
there would be no hangovers.

32:09.261 --> 32:11.804
We could do whatever
we wanted!

32:13.140 --> 32:14.515
That's true.

32:14.725 --> 32:17.852
We could do whatever we want.

32:20.272 --> 32:21.814
[BOTH SCREAMING]

32:23.442 --> 32:25.776
Hey, Phil, if we wanted
to hit mailboxes, we can
let Ralph drive!

32:25.944 --> 32:26.986
Ha, yeah.

32:28.071 --> 32:29.822
[SIREN WAILING]

32:30.907 --> 32:33.618
Oh, hey. Hey, Phil.

32:33.785 --> 32:35.369
I think they
want you to stop.

32:35.537 --> 32:36.579
Hang on!

32:37.456 --> 32:38.873
[TYRES SCREECHING]

32:42.252 --> 32:44.253
PHIL:
It's the same thing
your whole life.

32:44.713 --> 32:47.632
"Clean up your room! Stand up
straight! Pick up your feet!

32:48.091 --> 32:49.634
Take it like a man!

32:49.843 --> 32:51.510
Be nice to your sister!

32:52.346 --> 32:54.847
Don't mix beer and wine, ever!

32:55.140 --> 32:56.474
Oh, yeah.

32:56.642 --> 32:58.934
Don't drive on
the railroad tracks!"

32:59.144 --> 33:01.729
Well, Phil, that's one
I happen to agree with.

33:11.323 --> 33:13.449
I don't know, Gus.

33:13.700 --> 33:16.452
Sometimes I think
you just have to

33:16.703 --> 33:19.080
take the big chances.

33:19.498 --> 33:21.666
COP [OVER SPEAKER]:
This is the police!
Pull over immediately!

33:22.292 --> 33:25.252
Hey! We're talking in here!

33:25.462 --> 33:27.338
[TRAIN HORN BLARING]

33:27.756 --> 33:30.257
Uh, Phil.
Yeah, yeah. yeah.

33:30.425 --> 33:32.343
I'm betting he's
gonna swerve first.

33:35.097 --> 33:36.138
Phil.

33:37.516 --> 33:39.308
Phil!
Aah!

33:39.768 --> 33:41.852
[BOTH SCREAMING]

33:43.522 --> 33:45.189
[LAUGHING]

33:46.566 --> 33:49.860
I'm not gonna live by
their rules anymore!

33:50.070 --> 33:51.696
I noticed that.

33:51.905 --> 33:54.448
You make choices
and you live with them.

33:54.741 --> 33:56.659
[SIRENS WAILING]

33:56.868 --> 33:58.411
Ho-ho!

34:07.003 --> 34:10.255
Oh, oh, oh, oh.
Ow, my knee!

34:13.051 --> 34:14.844
Let me handle this.

34:16.429 --> 34:20.181
Yeah, three cheeseburgers,
two large fries,

34:20.434 --> 34:22.518
two chocolate shakes
and one large Coke.

34:22.728 --> 34:24.645
And some flapjacks!

34:24.896 --> 34:26.731
Too early for flapjacks?

34:32.987 --> 34:35.906
["I GOT YOU BABE"
PLAYING ON RADIO]

34:40.286 --> 34:41.579
Yes!

34:41.788 --> 34:44.456
Oh! Rise and shine, campers!

34:44.708 --> 34:47.626
Don't forget your booties,
because it's cold out there today!

34:47.793 --> 34:51.338
It's cold out there every day.
What is this, Miami Beach?

34:51.505 --> 34:52.672
Not hardly!

34:52.966 --> 34:55.050
[CLASSICAL MUSIC
PLAYING ON RADIO]

34:56.303 --> 34:58.679
Slept like a baby, thank you.
Oh--

34:58.847 --> 35:00.848
Would you--?
I'd love some of your coffee, please.

35:01.016 --> 35:02.808
I hope--
Flurries moving in a little bit later,

35:03.018 --> 35:04.977
but the blizzard's gonna hit
outside of town.

35:05.145 --> 35:06.687
Uh, Mrs. Lancaster?

35:06.855 --> 35:09.148
Was anybody looking for me
here this morning?

35:09.399 --> 35:12.818
Perhaps a state official?
Maybe a blue hat, gun, nightstick?

35:13.028 --> 35:15.946
Oh, no, no one like that!
Will there be?

35:16.156 --> 35:17.823
Apparently not.

35:19.951 --> 35:23.329
Will you hold
my room for me, please?
I'm gonna stay an extra day.

35:29.169 --> 35:31.170
Catch you tomorrow, pops.

35:32.047 --> 35:35.883
Hey! Phil? Phil?

35:36.092 --> 35:38.886
Hey! Phil Connors!
Ned?

36:10.168 --> 36:13.587
I like to see a man of
advancing years throwing
caution to the wind.

36:13.797 --> 36:16.090
It's inspiring, in a way.

36:16.883 --> 36:19.343
My years are not advancing
as fast as you might think.

36:19.886 --> 36:20.928
More coffee, hon?

36:21.388 --> 36:22.680
Yeah, just keep it coming, please.

36:23.014 --> 36:24.139
Sure thing.

36:24.307 --> 36:25.808
[DISHES CLATTERING]

36:25.976 --> 36:28.352
GUS:
Oh, jeez, real nice!
Just put that anywhere, pal!

36:28.520 --> 36:29.687
RALPH:
Good save!

36:29.855 --> 36:31.146
[BOTH APPLAUDING
AND LAUGHING]

36:32.065 --> 36:35.818
Don't you worry about cholesterol,
lung cancer, love handles?

36:38.154 --> 36:39.864
I don't worry about
anything anymore.

36:40.323 --> 36:42.616
What makes you so special?
Everybody worries about something.

36:43.076 --> 36:45.703
That's exactly what
makes me so special.

36:45.912 --> 36:47.705
I don't even
have to floss.

36:54.671 --> 36:55.838
Ugh.

36:57.424 --> 36:58.465
What?

37:00.302 --> 37:03.971
The wretch, concentered all in self

37:04.389 --> 37:06.724
Living, shall forfeit fair renown

37:07.142 --> 37:10.060
And doubly dying, shall go down

37:10.270 --> 37:13.272
To the vile dust
From whence he sprung

37:13.523 --> 37:17.568
Unwept, unhonored and unsung

37:18.194 --> 37:20.237
Sir Walter Scott.

37:20.447 --> 37:22.531
[LAUGHING]

37:23.366 --> 37:24.783
What, you don't like poetry?

37:25.535 --> 37:26.911
I love poetry!

37:27.120 --> 37:30.247
I just thought that was
Willard Scott. I was confused.

37:30.749 --> 37:33.208
You think I'm acting like this
because I'm egocentric?

37:33.460 --> 37:36.629
I know you're egocentric.
It's your defining characteristic.

37:38.214 --> 37:42.551
Uh, are you guys ready?
We'd better get going if we're
gonna stay ahead of the weather.

37:42.761 --> 37:43.802
Thanks, Larry.

37:43.970 --> 37:46.096
Well, would you like
a doggy bag?

37:46.556 --> 37:47.973
I'm gonna stay here
and finish.

37:48.183 --> 37:50.476
I thought you hated
this town.

37:50.685 --> 37:52.561
It's beginning to grow on me.

37:53.897 --> 37:55.189
Larry, quit staring.

37:55.523 --> 37:58.400
These are excellent.
Bon appétit.

38:08.870 --> 38:11.121
Hey, did you see the
groundhog this morning?

38:12.248 --> 38:14.458
Uh-huh. I never miss it.

38:14.751 --> 38:16.335
What's your name?

38:18.213 --> 38:20.297
Nancy Taylor. And you are?

38:20.507 --> 38:23.050
What high school did you go to?
What?

38:23.259 --> 38:24.843
High school.

38:25.679 --> 38:28.263
Lincoln, in Pittsburgh.
Who are you?

38:28.473 --> 38:31.684
Who was your
12th-grade English teacher?

38:31.935 --> 38:33.310
Are you kidding?

38:33.561 --> 38:35.771
No, no, no, in 12th grade,
your English teacher was--

38:35.981 --> 38:37.898
Mrs. Walsh.
Mrs. Walsh, yeah.

38:38.108 --> 38:41.110
Nancy. Lincoln. Walsh.

38:41.277 --> 38:42.695
Okay. Thanks very much.

38:42.862 --> 38:46.115
Hey. Hey.

38:48.410 --> 38:51.620
["PENNSYLVANIA POLKA"
PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS]

38:58.962 --> 39:00.546
Nancy?

39:01.423 --> 39:03.882
Nancy Taylor!

39:04.384 --> 39:06.593
Lincoln High School!

39:07.012 --> 39:09.680
I sat next to you in
Mrs. Walsh's English class!

39:09.848 --> 39:14.101
Oh, I'm sorry.
Phil Connors!

39:14.811 --> 39:17.855
Wow! That's amazing!
You don't remember me, do you?

39:19.232 --> 39:20.441
Um...

39:20.650 --> 39:22.192
I even asked you to the prom.

39:23.445 --> 39:25.195
Phil Connors?

39:25.739 --> 39:27.948
I was short and I've sprouted.

39:28.783 --> 39:30.784
Yeah.

39:31.119 --> 39:34.079
Gosh! How are you?

39:34.789 --> 39:35.831
Great.

39:36.082 --> 39:37.791
You look terrific!

39:38.084 --> 39:40.627
You look very,
very terrific!

39:40.795 --> 39:42.588
[LAUGHING]

39:42.756 --> 39:45.174
Listen, I gotta go
do this report.

39:45.341 --> 39:46.550
Are you a reporter?

39:46.718 --> 39:48.552
I'm a weatherman with
Channel 9, Pittsburgh.

39:48.720 --> 39:51.513
Wow. Gosh, I should
have known! That's great!

39:51.806 --> 39:53.474
But maybe later we could...

39:53.683 --> 39:54.933
Yeah, whatever!

39:55.268 --> 39:57.144
Stay right here.

39:57.312 --> 39:58.479
Promise me?
Yes.

39:58.646 --> 39:59.730
Okay, I'll be right back.
Okay.

39:59.898 --> 40:02.483
Wish me luck!
Good luck!

40:03.943 --> 40:06.028
[♪♪♪]

40:12.160 --> 40:13.660
[NANCY GIGGLING]

40:20.376 --> 40:21.668
Oh, Phil.

40:22.712 --> 40:24.088
Oh, Rita.

40:27.967 --> 40:29.176
Who's Rita?

40:29.677 --> 40:31.261
How should I know?

40:31.554 --> 40:34.098
What is this, some kind
of one-night stand?

40:34.349 --> 40:36.308
On the contrary, Nancy,

40:36.559 --> 40:39.812
I love you.
I've always loved you.

40:40.605 --> 40:43.107
This is gonna
seem sudden but...

40:44.484 --> 40:46.485
Nancy, will you be my wife?

40:49.155 --> 40:51.907
Oh, Phil...

40:53.368 --> 40:54.827
Rita.

40:55.662 --> 40:58.163
Nancy.
Whatever.

41:02.627 --> 41:04.419
A gust of wind.

41:04.587 --> 41:06.046
[WIND WHOOSHES]

41:06.756 --> 41:07.965
A dog barks.

41:08.133 --> 41:09.550
[DOG BARKS]

41:09.717 --> 41:11.176
Cue the truck.

41:11.469 --> 41:13.554
[♪♪♪]

41:18.893 --> 41:20.102
Exit Herman.

41:20.812 --> 41:22.688
Walk on to the bank.

41:22.939 --> 41:26.984
Exit Felix, and stand there with
a not-so-bright look on your face.

41:28.903 --> 41:30.904
All right, Doris. Come on.

41:31.573 --> 41:34.491
Hey, fix your bra, honey.
That's better.

41:35.368 --> 41:36.910
Felix!

41:37.162 --> 41:38.579
How you doing, Doris?

41:38.788 --> 41:41.373
Can I have a roll of quarters?

41:42.584 --> 41:47.212
Ten, nine, eight,

41:47.922 --> 41:52.551
car, six, five,

41:52.802 --> 41:54.928
quarters,

41:55.305 --> 41:56.597
three,

41:56.764 --> 41:58.891
two...

42:06.691 --> 42:07.858
Felix?

42:08.067 --> 42:11.653
Did I bring out two bags or one?
I don't know.

42:18.786 --> 42:20.871
[♪♪♪]

42:38.932 --> 42:41.475
I thought we were going
to a costume party.

42:41.726 --> 42:44.603
[IMITATING CLINT EASTWOOD]
It's like I said, I love this film.

42:44.854 --> 42:47.064
I've seen it over 100 times.

42:47.315 --> 42:48.357
Phil!

42:48.566 --> 42:52.319
Told you, call me "Bronco."

42:52.570 --> 42:54.363
Sorry, Bronco.

42:55.615 --> 42:57.282
Hi, Nancy.

43:01.496 --> 43:03.455
My own fiancée

43:03.706 --> 43:05.832
doesn't remember me.

43:07.335 --> 43:08.794
Hi.
Hi.

43:08.962 --> 43:11.505
That'll be one adult and, uh...

43:11.756 --> 43:15.008
Two adults.
Two adults, I guess.

43:17.804 --> 43:22.933
--groundhog who,
as legend has it, can predict
the coming of an early spring.

43:23.142 --> 43:25.894
So I guess the question we have
to ask ourselves today is,

43:26.145 --> 43:28.105
"Does Phil feel lucky?"

43:28.314 --> 43:31.108
Rita, if you only
had one day to live,

43:31.359 --> 43:32.985
what would you
do with it?

43:33.236 --> 43:35.779
I don't know, Phil.
What are you dying of?

43:36.030 --> 43:40.158
No, I mean, the whole world
is about to explode.

43:40.326 --> 43:41.743
What do you do?

43:41.953 --> 43:44.246
I just want to know
where to put the camera.

43:44.455 --> 43:46.957
What are you looking for, Phil?
A date for the weekend?

43:47.208 --> 43:50.043
No, I'm just
interested in you.

43:50.295 --> 43:52.546
You know, what do you want?
What do you like?

43:52.755 --> 43:54.631
What do you think about?

43:54.882 --> 43:57.175
What kind of men
are you interested in?

43:57.385 --> 43:59.219
What do you do for fun?

43:59.887 --> 44:03.140
Is this for real, Phil,
or are you just trying to
make me look like a fool?

44:03.349 --> 44:07.561
I'm just trying to talk
like normal people talk.
Isn't this how they talk?

44:07.770 --> 44:10.105
Close.
Okay, so talk to me.

44:10.356 --> 44:12.566
Let me buy you a cup of coffee.

44:14.736 --> 44:15.777
And a doughnut.

44:15.945 --> 44:17.571
All right.

44:19.949 --> 44:21.950
PHIL:
So, what do you want
out of life, anyway?

44:22.160 --> 44:23.702
[CHUCKLES]

44:23.870 --> 44:25.454
I guess I want what
everybody wants.

44:25.621 --> 44:29.875
You know, career,
love, marriage, children.

44:30.293 --> 44:31.752
Are you seeing anyone?

44:32.253 --> 44:36.923
I think this is getting too personal.
I don't think I'm ready to share this
with you.

44:38.092 --> 44:40.344
How about you?
What do you want?

44:41.512 --> 44:44.806
What I really want
is someone like you.

44:45.058 --> 44:46.350
Oh, please.

44:46.601 --> 44:48.769
Well, why not?
What are you looking for?

44:49.020 --> 44:50.354
Who's your perfect guy?

44:51.731 --> 44:55.734
Well, first of all, he's too
humble to know he's perfect.

44:57.070 --> 44:58.445
That's me.

44:58.696 --> 45:02.032
He's intelligent,
supportive, funny...

45:02.283 --> 45:04.493
Intelligent, supportive, funny.

45:04.744 --> 45:08.080
Me, me, me.

45:08.331 --> 45:11.124
He's romantic and courageous.

45:11.376 --> 45:12.626
Me also.

45:13.211 --> 45:16.797
He's got a good body
but he doesn't have to look
in the mirror every two minutes.

45:17.465 --> 45:22.302
I have a great body, and sometimes
I go months without looking.

45:24.806 --> 45:28.308
He's kind, sensitive and gentle.

45:28.851 --> 45:30.685
He's not afraid to cry
in front of me.

45:30.937 --> 45:33.522
This is a man we're
talking about, right?

45:33.773 --> 45:38.735
He likes animals, children,
and he'll change poopy diapers.

45:38.986 --> 45:41.363
Does he have to use
the word "poopy"?

45:41.572 --> 45:46.368
Oh, and he plays an instrument,
and he loves his mother.

45:47.620 --> 45:50.372
I am really close on this one.

45:51.165 --> 45:53.917
Really, really close.

45:58.381 --> 45:59.965
It's Phil Connors!

46:00.174 --> 46:01.466
Hello.

46:01.676 --> 46:03.510
Thanks for watching.

46:16.441 --> 46:19.609
So, what are the chances
of getting out today?

46:19.861 --> 46:22.112
Van still won't start.
Larry's working on it.

46:22.363 --> 46:23.780
Wouldn't you know it?

46:24.031 --> 46:25.824
Can I buy you a drink?

46:27.243 --> 46:31.121
Okay.
Jim Beam, ice, water.

46:31.956 --> 46:33.081
For you, miss?

46:33.541 --> 46:36.877
Sweet vermouth on the rocks
with a twist, please.

46:42.175 --> 46:44.426
What are the chances
of getting out of town today?

46:44.677 --> 46:47.095
Van still won't start.
Larry's working on it.

46:47.346 --> 46:48.972
Wouldn't you know it?

46:49.182 --> 46:51.057
Can I buy you a drink?

46:52.435 --> 46:53.768
Okay.

46:53.936 --> 46:56.646
Sweet vermouth, rocks,
with a twist, please.

46:56.856 --> 46:59.608
For you, miss?
The same.

47:00.443 --> 47:02.110
That's my favorite drink.

47:02.361 --> 47:04.112
Mine too.

47:04.363 --> 47:05.906
It always makes me
think of Rome.

47:06.157 --> 47:09.159
The way the sun hits
the buildings in the afternoon.

47:09.327 --> 47:10.911
Ah.

47:11.162 --> 47:13.163
Well, what should we drink to?

47:14.415 --> 47:16.333
To the groundhog!

47:16.584 --> 47:19.211
I always drink
to world peace.

47:28.137 --> 47:30.055
Can I buy you a drink?

47:31.265 --> 47:32.807
Okay.

47:32.975 --> 47:36.019
Sweet vermouth, rocks,
with a twist, please.

47:36.687 --> 47:38.396
BARTENDER:
For you, miss?

47:38.648 --> 47:40.315
The same.

47:40.942 --> 47:42.400
That's my favorite drink.

47:42.652 --> 47:44.236
Mine too.

47:45.446 --> 47:47.697
It always makes me
think of Rome.

47:47.949 --> 47:51.743
The way the sun hits
the buildings in the afternoon.

47:52.828 --> 47:54.663
Well, what should we drink to?

47:56.707 --> 47:59.876
I like to say a prayer
and drink to world peace.

48:01.837 --> 48:05.131
To world peace.
World peace.

48:07.468 --> 48:09.094
Amen.

48:13.683 --> 48:17.018
Mmm, this is wonderful.
See? Didn't I tell you?

48:17.228 --> 48:19.271
How do you know so much
about Punxsutawney?

48:19.480 --> 48:21.898
I spend a lot of time here.

48:22.066 --> 48:24.317
Small-town people are more real,
more down-to-earth.

48:24.485 --> 48:26.778
That's how I feel.
Really?

48:26.946 --> 48:28.280
Would you like to try
some white chocolate?

48:28.447 --> 48:30.156
Yuck, don't make me sick.

48:30.366 --> 48:31.575
No white chocolate.

48:31.784 --> 48:33.952
There is something
so familiar about this.

48:34.120 --> 48:37.038
Hm?
Do you ever have déjà vu?

48:37.290 --> 48:38.665
Didn't you just
ask me that?

48:38.833 --> 48:40.500
[LAUGHING]

48:43.462 --> 48:47.048
I think people place too much
emphasis on their careers.

48:47.258 --> 48:50.427
I wish we could all live
in the mountains at high altitude.

48:50.636 --> 48:54.347
That's where I see myself
in five years. How about you?

48:54.599 --> 48:57.434
Oh, I agree. I just like
to go with the flow.

48:57.643 --> 48:59.728
See where it leads me.

48:59.979 --> 49:01.813
Well, it's led you here.

49:02.023 --> 49:03.398
Mm-hm.

49:03.566 --> 49:07.235
Of course, it's about
a million miles from where
I started out in college.

49:07.486 --> 49:10.030
You weren't in broadcasting
or journalism?

49:10.197 --> 49:11.823
Mm-hm.

49:11.991 --> 49:15.118
Believe it or not, I studied
19th-century French poetry.

49:15.286 --> 49:16.328
[LAUGHS]

49:16.495 --> 49:18.079
What a waste of time!

49:18.289 --> 49:21.249
I mean, for someone else
that would be an incredible
waste of time.

49:21.500 --> 49:23.543
So bold of you
to choose that.

49:23.794 --> 49:27.464
It's incredible. You must be
a very, very strong person.

49:29.216 --> 49:32.719
PHIL:
I think people place too much
emphasis on their careers.

49:32.970 --> 49:37.515
Gosh, I wish we could
all live in the mountains.
At high altitudes.

49:37.767 --> 49:40.810
That's where I see myself
in five years. How about you?

49:40.978 --> 49:43.480
Oh, I agree. I just like
to go with the flow,

49:43.648 --> 49:45.398
Yeah?
see what happens.

49:45.650 --> 49:48.318
Well, it's gotten you here.
Uh-huh.

49:48.486 --> 49:51.196
Of course, it's a million miles
from where I started out in college.

49:51.364 --> 49:54.449
Oh, yeah, you weren't in
broadcasting or journalism
or anything like that?

49:54.617 --> 49:56.242
Uh-uh.
Hm.

49:56.535 --> 50:00.622
Believe it or not, I studied
19th-century French poetry.

50:05.044 --> 50:08.505
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

50:17.556 --> 50:18.848
You speak French.

50:19.392 --> 50:20.850
Oui.

50:22.436 --> 50:24.521
[BOTH GRUNTING]

50:24.689 --> 50:26.272
I haven't done this
since I was a kid.

50:26.440 --> 50:29.401
Me neither. It's fun!

50:29.694 --> 50:30.735
It's good, clean fun.

50:33.614 --> 50:37.117
I hope that one day I can do
this with my own children.

50:40.538 --> 50:42.789
Where'd you get that?

50:43.040 --> 50:45.667
Well, I went over
to the snowman shop.

50:47.503 --> 50:49.045
Hey, an assassin!

50:49.505 --> 50:51.089
I'll protect you,
Your Majesty!

50:51.590 --> 50:54.342
I shall die for you.
You shall not take her!

50:54.552 --> 50:55.844
Find cover, my lady!

50:56.053 --> 50:57.971
[LAUGHING]

50:58.180 --> 51:00.515
I'm getting some good ones.
Ooh, hey, there's a boy.

51:00.725 --> 51:03.059
That's a boy! Good try.

51:03.227 --> 51:04.269
RITA:
Help me!

51:05.479 --> 51:07.021
[LAUGHING]

51:09.358 --> 51:12.485
[RAY CHARLES'
"YOU DON'T KNOW ME" PLAYING]

51:37.720 --> 51:39.804
[INAUDIBLE DIALOG]

51:55.738 --> 51:57.697
[RITA LAUGHING]

51:57.865 --> 51:59.741
[SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

52:00.242 --> 52:02.619
Ah.
What?

52:02.870 --> 52:06.915
I'm just amazed,
and I'm not easily amazed.

52:07.166 --> 52:08.583
About what?

52:08.834 --> 52:11.586
How you can start a day
with one kind of expectation

52:11.796 --> 52:13.880
and end up
so completely different.

52:15.299 --> 52:18.468
Well, do you like the way
this day is turning out?

52:18.677 --> 52:21.095
I like it very much.

52:21.347 --> 52:24.849
It's a perfect day.
You couldn't have
planned a day like this.

52:25.017 --> 52:26.351
Well, you can.

52:26.560 --> 52:29.562
It just takes
an awful lot of work.

52:29.814 --> 52:32.023
Come on in. I want to
show you something.

52:32.233 --> 52:34.526
I don't think I should, Phil.
I don't think you should either.

52:34.777 --> 52:39.113
That's why I'm just gonna show
you this one thing, and kick you
right out. It'll just be one minute.

52:39.824 --> 52:41.908
[♪♪♪]

52:47.289 --> 52:49.541
It's just lovely.

52:59.927 --> 53:02.595
Would you like to sit
and stare at the fake fire?

53:02.763 --> 53:04.430
Okay.

53:07.351 --> 53:09.561
It's a really wonderful room.

53:09.812 --> 53:11.646
It is now.

53:18.571 --> 53:21.030
I don't know, Phil.
I don't think we should do this.

53:21.282 --> 53:22.907
I don't either.

53:25.619 --> 53:28.329
You know what,
on second thought,
I think we should.

53:29.164 --> 53:32.333
It's the perfect end
to a perfect day.

53:32.918 --> 53:35.837
Well, it's a little fast for me.

53:36.088 --> 53:37.505
Me too.

53:37.965 --> 53:40.216
Maybe I should go.

53:40.426 --> 53:42.343
Where would you go?

53:42.595 --> 53:43.970
Why?

53:44.179 --> 53:46.472
We've got a perfect fire.

53:46.765 --> 53:49.267
I've got some French
poetry here. Baudelaire...

53:49.435 --> 53:51.185
Mmm.
C'est fantastique.

53:51.353 --> 53:52.854
I will read to you.

53:53.606 --> 53:57.734
I've got some ice cream over on
the windowsill. Hold on a minute.

54:03.365 --> 54:04.490
Rocky road?

54:04.658 --> 54:06.200
I love rocky road.

54:06.452 --> 54:08.369
Yeah, I thought so.

54:08.662 --> 54:09.787
You have to stay.

54:09.955 --> 54:14.417
Oh, no, really, Phil, I'm tired.
We can see each other tomorrow.

54:14.668 --> 54:18.421
No, tonight.
It's gotta be tonight.

54:18.631 --> 54:21.507
No, Phil, really.

54:22.426 --> 54:25.678
Come on, just stay for
a while and if you like it,
stay for a while longer.

54:25.888 --> 54:28.014
And if you like that,
stay for a while longer.

54:28.223 --> 54:30.099
Let's not spoil it, okay?

54:30.351 --> 54:32.769
We're not spoiling it.
I don't want to spoil it either.

54:32.978 --> 54:35.897
You know I can't stay with you.

54:36.148 --> 54:39.233
Why not? I love you.

54:41.278 --> 54:43.404
You love me?
I love you.

54:43.656 --> 54:47.784
You don't even know me.
Oh, I know you. I know you.

54:49.328 --> 54:52.288
Oh, no. I can't believe
I fell for this!

54:52.539 --> 54:54.916
This whole day has
just been one long setup.

54:55.084 --> 54:56.125
No, it hasn't.

54:56.377 --> 54:59.128
And I ate fudge. Yuck!

54:59.421 --> 55:01.464
No white chocolate,
no fudge.

55:02.049 --> 55:05.051
What are you doing?
Are you making some kind
of list or something?

55:05.219 --> 55:06.552
No.
Did you call up my friends

55:06.720 --> 55:08.596
and ask them what I like
and what I don't like?

55:08.764 --> 55:10.431
No.
Is this what love is for you?

55:10.599 --> 55:12.642
No, this is real.
This is love.

55:12.851 --> 55:14.310
Stop saying that!

55:14.937 --> 55:16.479
You must be crazy.

55:16.730 --> 55:20.441
I could never love someone
like you, Phil, because you'll
never love anyone but yourself.

55:20.985 --> 55:24.570
That's not true.
I don't even like myself.
Give me another chance.

55:26.240 --> 55:28.866
That's for making me
care about you.

55:35.749 --> 55:37.458
PHIL:
I haven't done this
since I was a kid.

55:37.626 --> 55:39.544
RITA:
Me neither. It's fun.

55:39.753 --> 55:44.090
And good, clean fun too.
I think that's what's missing
in the world today, don't you?

55:44.341 --> 55:46.592
Gosh, I can't wait to do this
with my own children.

55:46.760 --> 55:48.803
Golly, I want kids,
lots of kids!

55:49.054 --> 55:52.890
I want to adopt,
I want to have my own kids,
I want to have foster kids.

55:53.142 --> 55:55.393
I got this over at Snowman City.

55:55.644 --> 55:58.479
Hey! Some kid just
threw a snowball at us.

55:58.731 --> 56:00.356
Come here!
Let's have some fun!
Come on, eh?

56:00.524 --> 56:01.566
[LAUGHING]

56:02.359 --> 56:06.571
Hey, kids, come on!
I wish these were my own
kids hitting me like this.

56:06.780 --> 56:08.448
Hey!

56:08.615 --> 56:11.826
Hey! Ow, ow! Are any
of you up for adoption?

56:12.536 --> 56:14.954
Hey, here's a humdinger
over here!

56:15.205 --> 56:17.248
Wasn't that great?

56:23.172 --> 56:25.506
[♪♪♪]

56:25.674 --> 56:27.300
Stop it!

57:07.674 --> 57:10.802
["PENNSYLVANIA POLKA"
PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS]

57:12.096 --> 57:14.097
RITA:
Phil! Over here!

57:16.475 --> 57:19.102
Where have you been?
You're missing all the fun.

57:19.353 --> 57:21.229
Phil, you look terrible.

57:21.897 --> 57:24.398
What happened?
Rough night?

57:25.651 --> 57:27.235
Yeah.

57:42.626 --> 57:44.293
Okay, campers.

57:44.711 --> 57:46.546
Rise and shine.

57:48.465 --> 57:52.135
And don't forget your booties,
because it's cold out there today.

57:53.053 --> 57:55.972
It's cold out there every day.

57:56.181 --> 57:58.724
ALEX TREBEK [ON TV]:
This country's largest lake,
Chapala,

57:58.892 --> 58:00.935
is located near
the city of Guadalajara.

58:01.103 --> 58:02.270
What is Mexico?

58:02.479 --> 58:03.521
TREBEK: Leslie.
What is Mexico?

58:03.730 --> 58:05.314
TREBEK: Correct.
Lakes and Rivers, 400.

58:05.941 --> 58:08.609
TREBEK:
Seneca is the largest of these
lakes in west-central New York.

58:09.278 --> 58:10.778
What are the Finger Lakes?
TREBEK: Jim.

58:10.988 --> 58:12.530
JIM: What are the Finger Lakes?
TREBEK: Correct.

58:12.698 --> 58:13.948
Amazing.

58:14.116 --> 58:18.286
TREBEK: This South American lake--
What is Titicaca?

58:18.453 --> 58:19.662
TREBEK: Jim.
JIM: What is Titicaca?

58:19.830 --> 58:21.539
TREBEK: Correct.
Lakes and Rivers for 1000.

58:21.707 --> 58:23.624
TREBEK: Milky-colored--
What is the Rhone?

58:23.792 --> 58:25.501
--when entering Lake Geneva,

58:25.752 --> 58:28.296
this river is
clear blue upon exiting.

58:28.463 --> 58:29.505
Jim?
What is the Rhone?

58:29.715 --> 58:31.048
TREBEK:
The Rhone. Good for $1000.

58:31.300 --> 58:33.718
You're $500 off the lead right now.

58:33.927 --> 58:36.012
Very good. Very good.

58:36.513 --> 58:38.181
This is pitiful.

58:38.515 --> 58:39.932
A thousand people

58:40.184 --> 58:43.186
freezing their butts off,
waiting to worship a rat.

58:43.395 --> 58:46.772
What a hype.
Groundhog Day used to
mean something in this town.

58:46.940 --> 58:49.692
They used to pull the hog out,
and they used to eat it.

58:49.902 --> 58:53.029
You're hypocrites! All of you!

58:55.324 --> 58:57.992
You got a problem with
what I'm saying, Larry?

58:58.160 --> 59:00.953
Untie your tongue and you
come out here and talk, huh?

59:01.121 --> 59:03.164
Am I upsetting you, princess?

59:03.373 --> 59:05.249
You know, you want
a prediction about the weather?

59:05.417 --> 59:08.085
You're asking the wrong Phil.

59:08.337 --> 59:11.005
I'll give you a winter prediction.

59:11.256 --> 59:13.299
It's gonna be cold.

59:13.550 --> 59:15.760
It's gonna be gray.

59:15.969 --> 59:20.765
And it's gonna last you
for the rest of your life.

59:21.308 --> 59:24.101
["I GOT YOU BABE"
PLAYING ON RADIO]

59:27.356 --> 59:30.066
["I GOT YOU BABE"
PLAYING ON RADIO]

59:39.326 --> 59:41.827
["I GOT YOU BABE"
PLAYING ON RADIO]

59:51.713 --> 59:54.006
["I GOT YOU BABE"
PLAYING ON RADIO]

59:55.592 --> 59:59.345
Once again the eyes of
the nation have turned here

59:59.846 --> 01:00:03.099
to this tiny village
in Western Pennsylvania.
Blah-blah-blah-blah.

01:00:03.308 --> 01:00:06.227
There is no way that this winter

01:00:06.478 --> 01:00:09.355
is ever going to end

01:00:09.564 --> 01:00:13.526
as long as this groundhog
keeps seeing his shadow.

01:00:13.777 --> 01:00:15.653
I don't see
any other way out.

01:00:16.446 --> 01:00:18.322
He's gotta be stopped.

01:00:19.825 --> 01:00:21.200
And I have to stop him.

01:00:23.745 --> 01:00:26.080
Real good, Phil. Real good.

01:00:27.666 --> 01:00:29.250
He's out of his gourd.

01:00:33.922 --> 01:00:37.091
I'm worried. I think
there's something
really wrong with Phil.

01:00:37.259 --> 01:00:40.219
Yeah, there's a lot of things
really wrong with Phil.

01:00:42.389 --> 01:00:43.764
Oh, hi, Phil.

01:00:43.932 --> 01:00:46.183
I've come to the end of me, Rita.

01:00:46.435 --> 01:00:48.561
There's no way out now.

01:00:50.022 --> 01:00:53.357
I just want you to remember we had
a beautiful day together once.

01:00:56.778 --> 01:00:58.195
All right, little fella.

01:00:58.447 --> 01:01:01.824
Good job. He just smiled at me!
Did you see that?

01:01:02.075 --> 01:01:03.576
I believe he did.

01:01:04.494 --> 01:01:07.330
Okay, little fella.
There you go.

01:01:09.333 --> 01:01:11.709
Hi, there, mister.
Something I can do you for?

01:01:14.296 --> 01:01:16.213
Hey! What are you doing?

01:01:16.423 --> 01:01:18.507
[♪♪♪]

01:01:20.969 --> 01:01:23.012
Get the word out.
Somebody kidnapped Phil!

01:01:23.388 --> 01:01:24.722
We're going after him!

01:01:28.268 --> 01:01:30.394
[TYRES SCREECHING]

01:01:31.396 --> 01:01:33.814
Why would anybody
steal a groundhog?

01:01:34.274 --> 01:01:37.276
I could probably think
of a couple of reasons.
Pervert.

01:01:43.325 --> 01:01:44.992
[TYRES SCREECHING]

01:02:03.303 --> 01:02:05.096
He must have just snapped!

01:02:05.305 --> 01:02:06.639
This ought to be good.

01:02:06.848 --> 01:02:08.808
[HORNS HONKING]

01:02:09.017 --> 01:02:10.267
RITA:
What is he doing?

01:02:10.477 --> 01:02:12.019
What can he be thinking?

01:02:12.687 --> 01:02:14.271
That's not bad
for a quadruped.

01:02:14.523 --> 01:02:18.442
You gotta check your mirrors.
Just the side of your eye.
Side of your eye.

01:02:22.656 --> 01:02:24.281
[SIREN WAILING]

01:02:24.491 --> 01:02:25.991
That's it. That's it.

01:02:26.243 --> 01:02:29.286
Hey, they're chasing us!
Come on, make it fun.

01:02:37.504 --> 01:02:38.671
Don't drive angry.

01:02:38.880 --> 01:02:40.089
Don't drive angry.

01:03:00.110 --> 01:03:02.987
Hot dog! There's no way out
except the way we came in!

01:03:03.238 --> 01:03:04.697
We got him now!

01:03:05.782 --> 01:03:08.075
[ENGINE REVVING]

01:03:08.869 --> 01:03:11.495
[♪♪♪]

01:03:24.009 --> 01:03:26.469
What the hell is he doing?
I don't know.

01:03:30.807 --> 01:03:33.601
If you gotta shoot, aim high.
I don't wanna hit the groundhog.

01:03:38.398 --> 01:03:40.149
Well, we mustn't keep
our public waiting, huh?

01:03:40.358 --> 01:03:41.984
[CHITTERING]

01:03:43.487 --> 01:03:44.820
It's showtime, Phil.

01:03:51.203 --> 01:03:52.495
All right, on me, Larry,
in three...

01:03:54.789 --> 01:03:56.248
two...

01:03:57.375 --> 01:03:58.417
one.

01:04:12.140 --> 01:04:13.641
Phil!

01:04:15.519 --> 01:04:16.894
He might be okay.

01:04:21.525 --> 01:04:24.068
Well, no. Probably not now.

01:04:32.619 --> 01:04:35.746
["I GOT YOU BABE"
PLAYING ON RADIO]

01:04:39.709 --> 01:04:41.418
Aw, nuts.

01:04:42.003 --> 01:04:44.505
[CLASSICAL MUSIC
PLAYING ON RADIO]

01:04:48.885 --> 01:04:51.804
Did you sleep well,
Mr. Connors?

01:04:52.847 --> 01:04:56.559
Would you like
some, uh, toast?

01:04:58.979 --> 01:05:01.063
[♪♪♪]

01:05:12.033 --> 01:05:14.034
[ELECTRICITY CRACKLING]

01:05:14.911 --> 01:05:17.329
Oh, my God.

01:05:19.916 --> 01:05:22.293
[HORN HONKING
AND TYRES SCREECHING]

01:05:49.571 --> 01:05:51.155
That's him.

01:05:54.117 --> 01:05:57.536
He was a really, really great guy.

01:05:57.787 --> 01:06:01.290
I really, really liked him a lot.

01:06:08.298 --> 01:06:10.299
I'm sorry?
What was that again?

01:06:10.717 --> 01:06:13.469
I'm a god.
You're God?

01:06:13.678 --> 01:06:16.930
I'm a god. I'm not the God,
I don't think.

01:06:17.515 --> 01:06:19.642
Because you survived a car wreck?

01:06:19.809 --> 01:06:21.060
You folks
ready to order?

01:06:21.269 --> 01:06:24.480
I didn't just survive a wreck.
I wasn't just blown up yesterday.

01:06:24.898 --> 01:06:27.483
I have been stabbed,
shot, poisoned,

01:06:27.692 --> 01:06:31.028
frozen, hung, electrocuted
and burned.

01:06:31.237 --> 01:06:32.571
Oh, really?

01:06:32.822 --> 01:06:37.034
Every morning I wake up
without a scratch on me,
not a dent in the fender.

01:06:37.744 --> 01:06:38.827
I am an immortal.

01:06:39.037 --> 01:06:41.664
Special today is blueberry waffles.

01:06:41.873 --> 01:06:43.707
Why are you telling me this?

01:06:44.000 --> 01:06:46.126
Because I want you
to believe in me.

01:06:46.336 --> 01:06:47.670
You're not a god.

01:06:47.879 --> 01:06:51.298
You can take my word for it.
This is 12 years of Catholic
school talking.

01:06:51.841 --> 01:06:53.801
I can come back
if you're not ready.

01:06:54.010 --> 01:06:55.511
How do you know
I'm not a god?

01:06:55.679 --> 01:06:57.471
Ha! Oh, please.

01:06:57.722 --> 01:07:00.057
How do you know?
Because it's not possible.

01:07:00.266 --> 01:07:02.017
I'll come back.

01:07:02.352 --> 01:07:03.602
Doris.

01:07:07.023 --> 01:07:09.608
This is Doris.
Her brother-in-law
Carl owns this diner.

01:07:09.859 --> 01:07:12.361
She's worked here since she was 17.
More than anything else in her life,

01:07:12.529 --> 01:07:14.405
she wants to see Paris
before she dies.

01:07:14.572 --> 01:07:16.115
Oh, boy, would I!

01:07:16.282 --> 01:07:17.324
What are you doing?

01:07:17.492 --> 01:07:18.992
This is Debbie Kleiser
and her fiancé, Fred.

01:07:19.244 --> 01:07:20.494
Do I know you?

01:07:20.662 --> 01:07:23.664
They're supposed to be getting
married this afternoon, but Debbie
is having second thoughts.

01:07:23.832 --> 01:07:24.998
What?

01:07:25.250 --> 01:07:26.375
Lovely ring.

01:07:26.626 --> 01:07:31.463
This is Bill. He's been a waiter
for three years, since he left
Penn State and had to get work.

01:07:31.631 --> 01:07:34.800
He likes the town,
he paints toy soldiers
and he's gay.

01:07:35.009 --> 01:07:36.510
I am.

01:07:36.678 --> 01:07:39.430
This is Gus. He hates his life here,
he wishes he'd stayed in the Navy.

01:07:39.681 --> 01:07:42.224
Well, I could've retired
on half pay after 20 years.

01:07:42.475 --> 01:07:44.309
Excuse me.
Is this some kind of trick?

01:07:44.561 --> 01:07:46.228
Well, maybe the real God
uses tricks.

01:07:46.396 --> 01:07:49.523
You know, maybe he's not
omnipotent, he's just been around
so long he knows everything.

01:07:49.691 --> 01:07:51.483
Oh, okay. Well, who's that?

01:07:51.651 --> 01:07:54.319
This is Tom.
He worked in the coal mine
till they closed it down.

01:07:54.487 --> 01:07:55.696
And her?
That's Alice.

01:07:55.864 --> 01:07:58.532
Came from Ireland when she
was a baby. She lived in Erie
most of her life.

01:07:58.700 --> 01:07:59.742
He's right.

01:07:59.909 --> 01:08:01.285
And her?
Nancy.

01:08:01.536 --> 01:08:04.621
She works in the dress shop,
and makes noises like a chipmunk
when she gets real excited.

01:08:04.789 --> 01:08:06.331
Hey!
It's true.

01:08:06.499 --> 01:08:09.418
How do you know these people?
I told you, I know everything.

01:08:09.669 --> 01:08:12.546
In about five seconds,
a waiter's gonna drop
a tray of dishes.

01:08:12.756 --> 01:08:15.507
Five, four, three, two, one.
This is nuts.

01:08:17.844 --> 01:08:20.261
Okay?
Okay, that's enough.

01:08:21.305 --> 01:08:23.515
What about me, Phil?
Do you know me too?

01:08:23.767 --> 01:08:27.978
I know all about you.
You like producing, but you hope
for more than Channel 9 Pittsburgh.

01:08:28.188 --> 01:08:30.606
Well, everyone knows that.

01:08:30.774 --> 01:08:32.566
You like boats but not the ocean.

01:08:32.734 --> 01:08:33.942
[♪♪♪]

01:08:34.109 --> 01:08:37.362
You go to a lake in the summer
with your family up in the mountains.

01:08:37.613 --> 01:08:41.533
There's a long wooden dock
and a boathouse with boards
missing from the roof,

01:08:42.243 --> 01:08:45.162
and a place you used to
crawl underneath to be alone.

01:08:45.788 --> 01:08:49.041
You're a sucker for
French poetry and rhinestones.

01:08:49.751 --> 01:08:51.167
You're very generous.

01:08:51.419 --> 01:08:53.921
You're kind to strangers
and children.

01:08:54.464 --> 01:08:57.299
And when you stand in the snow
you look like an angel.

01:08:57.759 --> 01:08:59.301
How are you doing this?

01:09:00.386 --> 01:09:05.265
I told you, I wake up
every day right here.

01:09:05.475 --> 01:09:08.894
Right in Punxsutawney.
And it's always February 2nd.

01:09:09.895 --> 01:09:12.397
And there's nothing
I can do about it.

01:09:13.107 --> 01:09:16.193
If you still can't
believe me, listen:

01:09:16.444 --> 01:09:18.444
In 10 seconds,

01:09:18.947 --> 01:09:22.407
Larry is gonna come through
that door and take you away
from me.

01:09:22.658 --> 01:09:25.285
But you can't let him.
Larry?

01:09:25.453 --> 01:09:28.538
Please believe me.
You've got to believe me.

01:09:33.627 --> 01:09:37.631
You guys ready? We'd better
get going if we're gonna stay
ahead of the weather.

01:09:38.258 --> 01:09:39.508
What's that?

01:09:40.426 --> 01:09:42.845
"--to stay ahead of the weather."

01:09:48.350 --> 01:09:50.060
RITA:
Maybe it really is happening.

01:09:50.228 --> 01:09:52.437
I mean, how else
could you know so much?

01:09:52.647 --> 01:09:55.148
PHIL:
Well, there is no way.
I'm not that smart.

01:09:56.276 --> 01:09:58.527
Maybe I should spend
the rest of day with you

01:09:58.778 --> 01:10:02.239
as an objective witness,
just to see what happens.

01:10:02.490 --> 01:10:04.950
Gee, this sounds like
a science project.

01:10:06.077 --> 01:10:07.286
PHIL:
Concentrate.

01:10:07.537 --> 01:10:09.329
You gotta want it.

01:10:09.789 --> 01:10:11.874
You've gotta want it, Rita.

01:10:12.333 --> 01:10:16.545
Oh, come on. It's more
in the wrist than the fingers.
You just gotta "pfft, pfft."

01:10:17.547 --> 01:10:19.214
Pfft, pfft.

01:10:24.512 --> 01:10:26.346
Be the hat. Come on, go.
Be the hat.

01:10:26.514 --> 01:10:28.348
It would take me a year
to get good at this.

01:10:28.516 --> 01:10:33.061
No, six months.
Four to five hours a day,
and you'd be an expert.

01:10:33.563 --> 01:10:37.190
Is this what you do with eternity?
Now you know.

01:10:38.610 --> 01:10:40.652
That's not the worst part.

01:10:40.904 --> 01:10:42.321
What's the worst part?

01:10:42.572 --> 01:10:47.326
The worst part is that
tomorrow you will have
forgotten all about this

01:10:47.493 --> 01:10:48.869
and you'll treat me
like a jerk again.

01:10:49.037 --> 01:10:50.704
No.

01:10:50.872 --> 01:10:52.372
It's all right, I am a jerk.

01:10:52.582 --> 01:10:54.416
No, you're not.

01:10:54.792 --> 01:10:59.296
It doesn't make any difference.
I've killed myself so many times,

01:10:59.547 --> 01:11:01.256
I don't even exist anymore.

01:11:01.841 --> 01:11:04.593
Well, sometimes I wish I had
a thousand lifetimes.

01:11:05.178 --> 01:11:08.180
I don't know, Phil.
Maybe it's not a curse.

01:11:08.431 --> 01:11:11.058
It just depends
on how you look at it.

01:11:12.602 --> 01:11:14.811
Gosh, you're
an upbeat lady!

01:11:18.107 --> 01:11:21.276
I want you to know it's been
a really nice day for me.

01:11:21.444 --> 01:11:22.486
Me too.

01:11:22.654 --> 01:11:27.741
And maybe, if it's not too boring,
we could do it again sometime.

01:11:27.992 --> 01:11:29.409
I hope so.

01:11:41.589 --> 01:11:43.382
You're still here.

01:11:44.842 --> 01:11:48.679
Oh, I thought you were supposed
to disappear. Or I was or something.

01:11:48.846 --> 01:11:52.808
Not until 6.
Oh! You rat!

01:11:53.059 --> 01:11:54.893
I never said midnight.

01:11:55.228 --> 01:11:57.688
You knew I was
waiting for midnight.

01:11:58.481 --> 01:11:59.898
Does this mean
you're gonna leave?

01:12:01.734 --> 01:12:03.026
No.

01:12:03.695 --> 01:12:04.820
Good.

01:12:06.698 --> 01:12:08.156
Okay.

01:12:08.324 --> 01:12:11.118
[♪♪♪]

01:12:15.498 --> 01:12:17.165
RITA:
I'm sorry.

01:12:18.668 --> 01:12:20.919
PHIL:
It's all right. You can fall asleep.

01:12:21.921 --> 01:12:24.256
I promise I won't touch you.

01:12:24.966 --> 01:12:26.508
Much.

01:12:27.552 --> 01:12:30.303
It's all right. I'm not tired.

01:12:31.139 --> 01:12:32.806
What were you saying?

01:12:34.225 --> 01:12:37.519
I think the last thing
that you heard was,

01:12:37.770 --> 01:12:40.439
"Only God could make a tree."

01:12:40.690 --> 01:12:41.773
Really?

01:13:19.937 --> 01:13:22.230
What I wanted to say was...

01:13:23.983 --> 01:13:26.109
I think you're the kindest,

01:13:26.360 --> 01:13:28.904
sweetest, prettiest person

01:13:29.405 --> 01:13:31.406
I've ever met in my life.

01:13:32.950 --> 01:13:35.160
I've never seen anyone

01:13:35.787 --> 01:13:38.288
that's nicer to people
than you are.

01:13:42.335 --> 01:13:43.794
Hm?

01:13:51.260 --> 01:13:53.303
And the first time I saw you

01:13:54.388 --> 01:13:56.640
something happened to me.

01:13:57.892 --> 01:14:00.018
I never told you...

01:14:03.397 --> 01:14:05.816
but I knew that
I wanted to hold you

01:14:06.025 --> 01:14:07.901
as hard as I could.

01:14:12.406 --> 01:14:13.698
[MOANS]

01:14:20.873 --> 01:14:23.333
I don't deserve
someone like you.

01:14:27.171 --> 01:14:28.964
But if I ever could...

01:14:30.424 --> 01:14:32.509
I swear I would love you

01:14:32.885 --> 01:14:35.011
for the rest of my life.

01:14:39.600 --> 01:14:41.476
Did you say something?

01:14:47.191 --> 01:14:48.775
Good night, Rita.

01:14:49.986 --> 01:14:51.570
Good night, Phil.

01:14:57.326 --> 01:15:00.078
["I GOT YOU BABE"
PLAYING ON RADIO]

01:15:16.429 --> 01:15:18.430
DJ 1:
Okay, campers, rise and shine!

01:15:18.598 --> 01:15:21.141
And don't forget your booties,
because it's cold out there!

01:15:21.309 --> 01:15:24.227
DJ 2:
It's cold out there every day.
What is this, Miami Beach?

01:15:24.395 --> 01:15:25.604
DJ 1:
Not hardly!

01:15:39.452 --> 01:15:42.579
["PENNSYLVANIA POLKA"
PLAYING OVER SPEAKERS]

01:16:01.015 --> 01:16:03.475
Who wants coffee?
Get it while it's hot.

01:16:03.643 --> 01:16:06.561
Oh. Thanks, Phil.
Larry?

01:16:06.812 --> 01:16:08.897
Skim milk, two sugar.

01:16:09.148 --> 01:16:10.482
Yeah. Thanks, Phil.

01:16:10.650 --> 01:16:11.858
Pastry?

01:16:12.109 --> 01:16:13.276
No. We're just setting up.

01:16:13.486 --> 01:16:15.278
Pastry, Larry?
Take your pick.

01:16:16.530 --> 01:16:18.573
Thanks, Phil. Raspberry. Great.

01:16:19.075 --> 01:16:22.244
See, I was just talking with
Buster Green, he's the head
groundhog honcho.

01:16:22.495 --> 01:16:25.288
And he said if we set up over here
we might get a better shot.

01:16:25.623 --> 01:16:26.790
What do you think?

01:16:26.958 --> 01:16:27.999
Sounds good.

01:16:28.334 --> 01:16:29.542
Larry, what do you think?

01:16:30.836 --> 01:16:32.754
Yeah. Let's go for it.

01:16:33.005 --> 01:16:34.047
Good work, Phil.

01:16:34.715 --> 01:16:38.051
Maybe we'll get lucky.
Let me give you a hand
with the heavy stuff.

01:16:39.512 --> 01:16:42.430
No, no. You got your coffee.
I'll get it.

01:16:43.724 --> 01:16:45.600
We never talk, Larry.
Do you have kids?

01:16:47.853 --> 01:16:52.023
[MOZART'S "PIANO SONATA
NO. 16 IN C MAJOR" PLAYING]

01:17:13.087 --> 01:17:14.546
[DOORBELL RINGS]

01:17:19.593 --> 01:17:22.220
Yes?
Yes, I'd like a piano lesson, please.

01:17:22.555 --> 01:17:26.224
Oh, okay. I'm with a student now.
But if you want to come back
tomorrow, I could probably--

01:17:26.392 --> 01:17:29.978
Well, I kind of want to get started.
I could give you $1000.

01:17:32.606 --> 01:17:33.648
Come on in.

01:17:46.037 --> 01:17:48.121
[SCALES PLAYING ON PIANO]

01:17:53.210 --> 01:17:55.253
Morning!
Off to see the groundhog?

01:17:55.463 --> 01:17:57.505
Buon giorno, signore!

01:17:58.507 --> 01:18:00.967
Think it's gonna be
an early spring?

01:18:01.218 --> 01:18:03.595
Winter, slumbering in the open air

01:18:03.846 --> 01:18:05.472
Wears on his smiling face

01:18:05.723 --> 01:18:07.932
A dream of spring

01:18:08.184 --> 01:18:09.768
Ciao!

01:18:10.519 --> 01:18:11.728
Ciao!

01:18:15.441 --> 01:18:17.525
[PIANO PLAYING OFF-KEY]

01:18:43.219 --> 01:18:45.095
Phil!

01:18:45.930 --> 01:18:49.015
Rita, hi.
Hey, Lar, hi.

01:18:49.850 --> 01:18:51.101
How does she look?

01:18:51.394 --> 01:18:52.477
Great.

01:18:52.853 --> 01:18:53.895
Thank you.

01:18:54.105 --> 01:18:57.565
Did you know he could ice sculpt?
No.

01:18:57.983 --> 01:19:01.736
[PLAYING RACHMANINOFF'S
"18TH VARIATION FROM RAPSODIE
ON A THEME OF PAGANINI"]

01:19:11.622 --> 01:19:14.833
Not bad, Mr. Connors.
You say this is your first lesson?

01:19:15.793 --> 01:19:19.045
Yes, but my father
was a piano mover, so...

01:19:23.676 --> 01:19:26.970
Phil? Phil Connors,
I thought it was you.

01:19:27.138 --> 01:19:29.472
Ned Ryerson.
Yes.

01:19:31.183 --> 01:19:33.726
I have missed you so much.

01:19:38.107 --> 01:19:41.651
I don't know where you're headed,
but can you call in sick?

01:19:41.861 --> 01:19:43.111
Uh...

01:19:43.279 --> 01:19:44.904
[CHUCKLES]

01:19:45.072 --> 01:19:46.990
I gotta get going.

01:19:47.867 --> 01:19:49.909
It's good to see you, Phil.

01:19:54.373 --> 01:19:56.458
[♪♪♪]

01:20:08.012 --> 01:20:09.471
Hello, father.

01:20:10.222 --> 01:20:11.931
Let's get you
someplace warm.

01:20:12.183 --> 01:20:15.143
Yeah. Yeah.
Remember me?

01:20:20.733 --> 01:20:23.234
Sir? Are you the one who
brought the old man in?

01:20:23.402 --> 01:20:25.487
Mm-hm. How is he?

01:20:25.654 --> 01:20:27.322
Well, he just passed away.

01:20:27.490 --> 01:20:29.240
[♪♪♪]

01:20:29.408 --> 01:20:32.452
What did he die of?
He was just old.

01:20:32.703 --> 01:20:34.537
It was just his time.

01:20:37.291 --> 01:20:40.293
I want to see his chart. Excuse me.
Um, sir!

01:20:40.669 --> 01:20:42.295
Sir, you can't come in here.

01:20:42.546 --> 01:20:45.173
Sir, this is a restricted area.

01:20:54.350 --> 01:20:56.017
Where's the chart?

01:20:56.519 --> 01:20:58.853
Sometimes people just die.

01:20:59.772 --> 01:21:01.231
Not today.

01:21:13.619 --> 01:21:15.828
Gets hard down there
at the bottom.

01:21:18.749 --> 01:21:19.958
Here you go.

01:21:20.292 --> 01:21:22.001
Thank you.

01:21:25.839 --> 01:21:28.550
Come on, dad.
Come on, pop. Come on, pop.

01:21:30.511 --> 01:21:32.303
Come on. Come on, breathe.

01:21:32.555 --> 01:21:35.223
Breathe, pop! Breathe, pop!

01:22:00.958 --> 01:22:03.626
PHIL:
When Chekhov saw the long winter,

01:22:04.086 --> 01:22:07.463
he saw a winter bleak
and dark and bereft of hope.

01:22:07.715 --> 01:22:12.385
Yet we know that winter is just
another step in the cycle of life.

01:22:12.636 --> 01:22:16.306
But standing here among
the people of Punxsutawney

01:22:16.515 --> 01:22:19.350
and basking in the warmth
of their hearths and hearts,

01:22:20.436 --> 01:22:22.729
I couldn't imagine a better fate

01:22:22.938 --> 01:22:25.898
than a long and lustrous winter.

01:22:26.150 --> 01:22:28.943
From Punxsutawney,
it's Phil Connors.

01:22:29.194 --> 01:22:30.486
So long.

01:22:32.364 --> 01:22:34.073
Nice speech, Phil.
Very nice.

01:22:34.325 --> 01:22:35.575
Thank you.

01:22:35.743 --> 01:22:40.079
Thanks. How was that for you two?
My man, you touched me.

01:22:40.331 --> 01:22:41.998
Thanks, Larry.
Thank you.

01:22:43.250 --> 01:22:44.459
I gotta go.

01:22:44.627 --> 01:22:45.710
Phil.
Hm?

01:22:45.878 --> 01:22:49.922
That was surprising.
I didn't know you were
so versatile.

01:22:50.090 --> 01:22:51.841
I surprise myself
sometimes.

01:22:52.051 --> 01:22:54.218
Where are you going?
Would you like to get
a cup of coffee?

01:22:54.386 --> 01:22:58.222
I'd love to. Can I have
a rain check? I've got some
errands I've gotta run. Okay?

01:23:00.684 --> 01:23:03.895
Phil? Errands? What errands?

01:23:04.146 --> 01:23:06.356
I thought we were going back.

01:23:07.650 --> 01:23:09.734
[♪♪♪]

01:23:15.074 --> 01:23:16.115
[YELLS]

01:23:19.620 --> 01:23:21.537
[SCREAMS]

01:23:23.999 --> 01:23:26.834
What do you say?
What do you say?
What do you say?

01:23:27.044 --> 01:23:29.921
You little brat.
You have never thanked me!

01:23:30.631 --> 01:23:32.256
I'll see you tomorrow.

01:23:32.424 --> 01:23:33.591
Maybe.

01:23:41.308 --> 01:23:43.643
You totaled it.

01:23:43.852 --> 01:23:47.271
It's only a flat tire.
What are we going to do?

01:23:47.439 --> 01:23:49.190
[ALL GASPING]

01:23:49.358 --> 01:23:52.777
It's an earthquake!
Oh, it's not an earthquake.

01:23:52.986 --> 01:23:54.487
WOMAN:
What is it?

01:23:56.490 --> 01:23:59.659
Oh! Thank you, young man.

01:24:00.786 --> 01:24:03.162
It's nothing, ma'am.
I had the tire and the jack.

01:24:03.414 --> 01:24:06.040
Just be comfortable, all right?
It'll be a minute.

01:24:06.291 --> 01:24:07.500
Who is that?

01:24:07.751 --> 01:24:10.503
He must be from
the motor club.

01:24:11.755 --> 01:24:14.424
WOMAN:
Oh, my God, he is having
a heart attack! Do something!

01:24:14.675 --> 01:24:18.761
Call 411, an ambulance,
a lawyer, doctor, anything,
oh, my God!

01:24:23.475 --> 01:24:25.309
[BUSTER GASPING]

01:24:26.019 --> 01:24:27.562
I think that did it.

01:24:31.442 --> 01:24:34.318
If you're gonna eat steak,
get sharper teeth.

01:24:34.570 --> 01:24:36.904
Enjoy your meal.
Thank you.

01:24:37.489 --> 01:24:38.823
Who was that?

01:24:39.032 --> 01:24:41.659
I'm fine, I'm fine.
WOMAN: Are you sure?

01:24:41.827 --> 01:24:42.869
BUSTER:
Eat, eat!

01:24:47.291 --> 01:24:48.833
LARRY:
Well, people just don't understand

01:24:49.042 --> 01:24:51.836
what is involved in this.
This is an art form.

01:24:52.087 --> 01:24:54.547
You know, I think that
most people just think

01:24:54.798 --> 01:24:57.967
that I hold a camera
and point it at stuff.

01:24:58.218 --> 01:25:00.511
There is a heck of a lot
more to it than just that.

01:25:01.305 --> 01:25:05.516
Hey, would you be at all interested
in seeing the inside of a van?

01:25:05.684 --> 01:25:09.562
Oh, you know, I really
have to get back to the party.

01:25:09.730 --> 01:25:11.522
Great idea.
I think I'll go with you.

01:25:11.690 --> 01:25:13.524
Let me just drop a tip here.

01:25:13.692 --> 01:25:15.401
Okay.

01:25:19.448 --> 01:25:21.532
Rita, hi. How are you?
Hi.

01:25:21.700 --> 01:25:22.742
Rita, this is Nancy.

01:25:22.910 --> 01:25:24.577
BOTH: Hi.
Nancy, Rita.

01:25:24.745 --> 01:25:26.829
We were just gonna go
to the party. You gonna go?

01:25:26.997 --> 01:25:29.248
Yeah, sounds like fun.
Maybe we should call Phil.

01:25:29.416 --> 01:25:32.293
Phil Connors?
I think he's already in there.

01:25:32.461 --> 01:25:34.003
Great.

01:25:35.088 --> 01:25:38.633
[BAND PLAYING
ROCK 'N' ROLL MUSIC]

01:26:23.929 --> 01:26:25.429
[CROWD APPLAUDING]

01:26:28.892 --> 01:26:32.019
[PLAYING RACHMANINOFF'S
"18TH VARIATION FROM RAPSODIE
ON A THEME OF PAGANINI"]

01:26:42.239 --> 01:26:44.740
[BAND PLAYING JAZZ MUSIC]

01:27:23.155 --> 01:27:24.822
[CROWD CHEERING]

01:27:29.703 --> 01:27:30.953
Isn't he good?

01:27:31.204 --> 01:27:32.330
He's great!

01:27:32.581 --> 01:27:34.206
He's my student.

01:27:36.835 --> 01:27:38.711
I'm so proud.

01:27:39.880 --> 01:27:41.547
Thank you.

01:27:42.257 --> 01:27:44.300
Hello, welcome to our party.

01:27:44.551 --> 01:27:46.802
Phil, I didn't know
you could play like that.

01:27:47.054 --> 01:27:48.763
Oh, I'm versatile.

01:27:48.931 --> 01:27:51.015
[BAND PLAYING JAZZ MUSIC]

01:27:56.146 --> 01:27:59.190
It's that nice young man
from the motor club.

01:27:59.399 --> 01:28:00.900
Thank you again.

01:28:01.151 --> 01:28:02.568
It's nothing, ladies.

01:28:02.819 --> 01:28:06.072
He's the fastest jack
in Jefferson County.

01:28:08.533 --> 01:28:10.159
What was that all about?

01:28:10.410 --> 01:28:13.496
I really don't know. They've been
hitting on me all night.

01:28:14.373 --> 01:28:15.748
There you are!

01:28:17.709 --> 01:28:20.920
I never thanked you properly
for what you did for Buster.

01:28:21.171 --> 01:28:23.214
Well, he would've
choked for sure.

01:28:23.465 --> 01:28:27.176
Well, he may have.
He was trying to swallow
a whole cow.

01:28:27.427 --> 01:28:28.636
I owe you one, buddy.

01:28:28.887 --> 01:28:32.014
Hang on to him, dear.
He's a real find.

01:28:34.434 --> 01:28:36.143
What did you do today?

01:28:36.395 --> 01:28:37.979
Oh, same old, same old.

01:28:43.735 --> 01:28:45.277
FRED:
Excuse me, Mr. Connors.

01:28:45.487 --> 01:28:47.071
Hey, Fred,
how was the wedding?

01:28:47.322 --> 01:28:50.324
Well, I just wanted to thank you
for making Debbie go through
with it and everything.

01:28:50.575 --> 01:28:53.619
All I did was fan the flame
of her passion for you, Fred.

01:28:53.870 --> 01:28:55.079
You are the best.

01:28:55.330 --> 01:28:56.372
No, you're the best.

01:28:56.623 --> 01:28:58.541
Rita, this is Debbie
and Fred Kleiser.

01:28:58.709 --> 01:28:59.875
Hi.

01:29:00.043 --> 01:29:01.502
Here you go, kids.
Congratulations.

01:29:01.670 --> 01:29:04.171
What is this? Oh, no way.

01:29:04.339 --> 01:29:06.173
No way!

01:29:06.425 --> 01:29:10.344
WrestleMania!
No way! No way! Ha-ha!

01:29:10.512 --> 01:29:13.472
How did you know?
We'll be in Pittsburgh anyway!

01:29:13.724 --> 01:29:15.558
Thank you, Mr. Connors.
You're a real pal.

01:29:15.809 --> 01:29:17.685
Oh, this is the best.

01:29:22.482 --> 01:29:23.899
I don't understand.

01:29:24.151 --> 01:29:25.860
Uh, yeah, I guess not.

01:29:26.361 --> 01:29:28.863
How does everyone know you?
I mean, you only come here
once a year,

01:29:29.031 --> 01:29:31.198
and you seem like the most
popular person in town.

01:29:31.450 --> 01:29:33.659
Excuse me, Dr. Connors?
Yes. Yes.

01:29:33.869 --> 01:29:36.787
I want to thank you
for fixing Felix's back.

01:29:36.997 --> 01:29:39.081
He can even help
around the house again.

01:29:39.291 --> 01:29:41.792
Well, I'm sorry
to hear that, Felix.

01:29:44.171 --> 01:29:45.796
Dr. Connors?

01:29:46.173 --> 01:29:48.507
It's kind of an honorary title.

01:29:48.759 --> 01:29:50.342
What is going on?

01:29:50.552 --> 01:29:51.594
I really don't know.

01:29:51.845 --> 01:29:54.305
No, there is something
going on with you.

01:29:54.890 --> 01:29:56.849
Would you like the long version
or the short one?

01:29:57.100 --> 01:29:59.935
Let's start with the short
and go from there.

01:30:00.145 --> 01:30:02.021
[SONG ENDS]

01:30:05.734 --> 01:30:07.735
Okay, folks,
attention.

01:30:08.528 --> 01:30:11.655
Time for the big bachelor auction.
Now, you all know the rules.

01:30:11.907 --> 01:30:14.366
All the eligible bachelors
come down in front.

01:30:14.659 --> 01:30:16.118
And you ladies,

01:30:16.369 --> 01:30:17.703
you bid on them!

01:30:17.954 --> 01:30:19.997
And you get to do whatever
you want with them,

01:30:20.165 --> 01:30:21.832
no questions asked!

01:30:22.084 --> 01:30:25.169
I don't want to know about it,
as long as it's legal.

01:30:25.378 --> 01:30:29.757
Okay, so get out your pocketbooks,
and remember it's all for charity.

01:30:29.925 --> 01:30:31.509
Phil!

01:30:31.927 --> 01:30:33.511
What are you doing down here?

01:30:33.762 --> 01:30:35.262
Go on, get up there.

01:30:35.472 --> 01:30:38.557
I got 10 bucks
that says you're mine.

01:30:38.975 --> 01:30:40.893
Hey, Buster,
I got your first victim.

01:30:41.103 --> 01:30:43.771
Phil Connors,
come on up here!

01:30:43.939 --> 01:30:46.524
[BAND PLAYS FANFARE]

01:30:48.819 --> 01:30:52.154
All right! Now, what am I bid
for this fine specimen?

01:30:52.447 --> 01:30:53.864
Five dollars!

01:30:54.074 --> 01:30:56.033
The bidding has
begun at $5.

01:30:56.326 --> 01:30:57.576
Ten dollars!

01:30:57.786 --> 01:30:58.994
Fifteen!

01:30:59.204 --> 01:31:01.205
Twenty!
Twenty-five!

01:31:01.373 --> 01:31:02.414
Thirty!

01:31:02.582 --> 01:31:04.375
DORIS: Thirty-five!
NANCY: Forty!

01:31:04.543 --> 01:31:05.584
DORIS:
Forty-five!

01:31:06.253 --> 01:31:07.294
NANCY:
Fifty!

01:31:07.504 --> 01:31:08.546
Fifty-five!

01:31:08.713 --> 01:31:09.755
Sixty!

01:31:09.923 --> 01:31:11.590
I'm bid $60.
Do I hear more?

01:31:15.387 --> 01:31:17.805
$339.88.

01:31:17.973 --> 01:31:20.057
[CROWD GASPING]

01:31:20.517 --> 01:31:22.268
[CROWD APPLAUDING]

01:31:22.477 --> 01:31:24.562
I don't think we're gonna
accept any more bids.

01:31:24.729 --> 01:31:30.234
I think that's sold
to the little lady for $339.88!

01:31:31.361 --> 01:31:32.736
Congratulations!

01:31:32.946 --> 01:31:34.363
[BAND PLAYING JAZZ MUSIC]

01:31:40.829 --> 01:31:42.746
BUSTER:
Okay, bachelors, who's next?

01:31:48.795 --> 01:31:50.754
[DRUMS PLAYING]

01:31:53.175 --> 01:31:56.468
BUSTER:
All right! Now, what
am I bid for this guy?

01:31:56.678 --> 01:31:58.512
Do I hear a buck and a half?

01:31:58.805 --> 01:32:00.055
Anybody?

01:32:00.932 --> 01:32:01.974
Seventy-five cents?

01:32:02.184 --> 01:32:03.976
I bid two bits!

01:32:04.603 --> 01:32:06.979
Sold to the lady for 25 cents.

01:32:07.189 --> 01:32:08.731
I got him!

01:32:15.238 --> 01:32:19.700
Phil? Phil? Phil Connors,
I thought that was you.

01:32:19.951 --> 01:32:22.411
Rita, this is Ned Ryerson,
he's my new insurance agent.

01:32:22.662 --> 01:32:23.913
I'll say.

01:32:25.123 --> 01:32:27.082
I have not seen this guy
for 20 years.

01:32:27.334 --> 01:32:32.379
He comes up to me and then
he buys whole life, term, fire,
theft, auto, dental, health,

01:32:32.589 --> 01:32:35.507
with the optional death
and dismemberment plan.
Water damage.

01:32:35.759 --> 01:32:37.927
Phil, this is the
best day of my life.

01:32:38.178 --> 01:32:40.304
Mine too.
Mine too.

01:32:40.513 --> 01:32:43.724
Where are we going?
Oh, let's not spoil it.

01:32:43.934 --> 01:32:45.100
[LAUGHING]

01:32:45.268 --> 01:32:49.313
Let's not-- I got that. Reow!

01:32:50.815 --> 01:32:52.233
Why can't I look?

01:32:52.692 --> 01:32:54.526
Because you
bother me a lot.

01:32:54.819 --> 01:32:56.195
I'm getting cold.

01:32:56.404 --> 01:32:58.030
How much longer
do I have to sit here?

01:32:58.657 --> 01:33:01.784
I'm just trying to give
you your money's worth.
You paid top dollar for me.

01:33:02.369 --> 01:33:04.703
Well, I think you were a bargain.

01:33:05.538 --> 01:33:07.665
Sweet of you to say.
You're probably right.

01:33:07.874 --> 01:33:09.959
[LAUGHING]

01:33:10.418 --> 01:33:11.835
Is it finished yet?

01:33:12.712 --> 01:33:16.840
Almost. I still have to put
some cherry syrup on the top
and then we can eat it.

01:33:17.092 --> 01:33:19.760
Come on, Phil.
I'm freezing!

01:33:19.970 --> 01:33:21.637
One second, one second.

01:33:21.888 --> 01:33:23.681
Let me turn it in the light.

01:33:23.848 --> 01:33:25.933
[♪♪♪]

01:33:29.187 --> 01:33:30.688
RITA:
It's amazing.

01:33:31.439 --> 01:33:32.690
It's beautiful.

01:33:36.987 --> 01:33:38.362
How did you do that?

01:33:39.197 --> 01:33:42.992
I know your face so well,
I could have done it with
my eyes closed.

01:33:47.539 --> 01:33:48.956
It's lovely.

01:33:49.708 --> 01:33:51.542
I don't know what to say.

01:33:52.752 --> 01:33:53.961
I do.

01:33:56.047 --> 01:33:58.340
No matter what
happens tomorrow,

01:33:58.591 --> 01:34:00.467
or for the rest of my life,

01:34:00.677 --> 01:34:02.720
I'm happy now...

01:34:03.596 --> 01:34:05.180
because I love you.

01:34:06.099 --> 01:34:07.891
I think I'm happy too.

01:34:49.684 --> 01:34:53.270
["I GOT YOU BABE"
PLAYING ON RADIO]

